definition: Biological or chemical events, or a series thereof, leading to a known function or end-product.
Naturally-occurring molecular events or a series thereof, leading to a known function or end-product.
Biological or chemical events or a series thereof, leading to a known function or end-product within an organism.
A linked series of chemical reactions that occur in a defined order within or between organism cells, and lead to a known function or end product.
A defined chemical event that occurs within or between organism cells.
A biological process occurring at the subcellular level, involving biochemical reactions.
A biological process occurring within a cell or its surroundings.
A biological process occurring in multiple cells, of similar or different type.
A biological process occurring in an organ, a system or at the organism level.
A biological process occurring at any anatomical level, and is abnormal or harmful to the organism.
A series of events that occur naturally in the environment and not within an organism.
A series of molecular events that involve at least one synthetic reaction.
The purpose or function assumed by a chemical, either naturally or as intended by humans .

The biological function of a chemical.  the biological role answers the question how a chemical is involved in molecular processes in an organism. this can include biochemical effects of non-endogenous chemicals, which are also assigned an industrial application such as pharmaceuticals. the biological role is limited to cellular levls, and will not include role at system process level, such as a chemical which has a role in a disease.
a chemical substance that  inhibits or activates a biological or chemical entity or process.
Substances that  inhibit  the catalytic activity  of enzymes.
a chemical substance that is involved in transmission of biochemical signals.
The assumed function of a chemical utilized by human.
A pharmacologic activity for which a chemical substance is utilized owing to its biological role.
A chemical substance used to destroy or control uwanted microorganisms such as fungi, bacteria and algae.
An agriculture-related purpose for which a chemical substance is utilized.
A chemical substance or preparation used to kill or control pests, such as insects, weeds, plant pathogens, rodents, etc.
A chemical purpose related to manufacturing of food and nutrition products.
Cosmetics and personal hygene products in which a chemical was incorportaed during  the manufacturing process.
A compnent utilized by the building and infrastructure inductry, which incorporates a chemical substance. .
A product used in the home environment, which includes a chemical substance.
An indirect function of a chemical which affect the physiological state of any organism (apart from the source organism, if of biological source).
A direct or indirect function of chemical product or process which affect the components of the environment.
The effect on an organism physiology, resulting from its exposure to a chemical.
A health condition or observation associated with a stimuli or with a biological activity of a chemical.
A health effect that consists on short or long-term disease, condition, disorder, syndrome or constant abnormality.
A group of disorders characterized by the presense of malignant neoplasm.
Any disorder (non-neoplastic or neoplastic) that affects the liver and the biliary system.
Any disorder that affects the heart.

A group of disorders characterized by behavioral and/or psychological abnormalities, often accompanied by physical symptoms. the symptoms may cause clinically significant distress or impairment in social and occupational areas of functioning. representative examples include anxiety disorders, cognitive disorders, mood disorders and schizophrenia. (nci).
Any disorder (non-neoplastic or neoplastic) that affects the gastrointestinal tract.
Any disorder that affects the blood vessels.
Any damage inflicted on the body.
Any disorder (non-neoplastic or neoplastic) that affects the brain, spinal cord, or peripheral nerves.

Any disorder that affects the endocrine system. it can be neoplastic (carcinoid tumor, neuroendocrine carcinoma, and pheochromocytoma) or non-neoplastic (such as diabetes mellitus, hyperthyroidism, and adrenal gland insufficiency).
Any disorder (non-neoplastic or neoplastic)  that affects the respiratory system or the thorax including the mediastinum and the heart. (nci).

Any disorder (non-neoplastic or neoplastic) that affects the male or female genital system. representative examples of non-neoplastic disorders include infection, testicular torsion, endometriosis, and adenomyosis. representative examples of neoplastic disorders include germ cell tumors, carcinoma, lymphoma, and sarcoma. (nci).
Any deviation from the normal structure or function of the hematopoietic or lymphoid system, that is manifested by a characteristic set of symptoms and signs. (nci).
A group of disorders, inherited or not, that result in a metabolic malfunction.
Any disorder (non-neoplastic or neoplastic) that affects muscles, bones and other connective tissue.
Any disorder that affects the ear or the labyrinth.

term: General disorders and administration site conditions
definition: Any disorder that was not classified under a specific system.
Any disorder that affects the eye. it can be neoplastic or non-neoplastic, such as conjunctivitis, glaucoma, cataract, conjunctival squamous cell carcinoma, uveal melanoma, and retinoblastoma.
Any  disorder resulting from the presence and activity of a microbial, viral, or parasitic agent. it can be transmitted by direct or indirect contact. (nci).
Any disorder that affects the kidneys and the urologic system.
Any deviation from the normal structure or function of the skin or subcutaneous tissue that is manifested by a characteristic set of symptoms and signs. (nci).

A group of disorders (non-neoplastic or neoplastic) that result  from the deregulation and/or deficiency of immune system functions. it includes autoimmune disorders (e.g., lupus erythematosus, dermatomyositis, rheumatoid arthritis), congenital and acquired immunodeficiency syndromes including the acquired immune deficiency syndrome (aids), and neoplasms (e.g., lymphomas and malignancies secondary to transplantation). (nci).
A short term health effect which reflects the reponse of the body to stimuli or is a symptom of a disease or condition; also includes health status which reflects stage in life.
The act or process of a systematic and thorough examination; research, study; the process of inquiring into or following up, intended to develop facts. (nci).
Human sensual perception of chemical stimuli.
Sensual perception of volatile chemicals reacting with the human olfactory system.
Sensual perception of chemicals reacting with the human oral taste sensors.
Sensual perception of obtained by the human visual sensors.
Sensual perception obtained by the human somatosensory system.
A concept that describes the origin of a chemical, its location within an organism, or its route of exposure.
The physiological origin within an organism, including anatomical compnents, biofluids and excreta.
An anatomical organizational level comprising of multiple organs and substructure, which serve a complete biological function.
An anatomical organizational level including multiple tissues or substructures, which enables a common biological function.
An anatomical organizational level including multiple cells yet not comprising a complete organ .
An anatomical organizational level including a component within a biological cell .
A liquid, semi-solid or solid material originating in the body.

An anatomical organizational level comprising of a single cell (or a fragment in some exceptions). a cell is defined by its type or function. it is the smallest unit of living structure capable of independent existence, composed of a membrane-enclosed mass of protoplasm and containing a nucleus or nucleoid.
Natural or synthetic origin of a chemical.
A living organism (species or a higher taxonomy rank), in which a chemical can be found.
A living organism belonging to the kingdom animalia. it feeds on organic matter, typically having specialized sense organs and nervous system and able to respond rapidly to stimuli.

A living organism belonging to the kingdom plantea. typically, it grows in a permanent site, absorbs water and inorganic substances through its roots, and synthesizes nutrients in its leaves by photosynthesis using the green pigment chlorophyll. examples incude trees, shrubs, herbs, grasses, ferns, and mosses.
A living organism that is of a microscopic scale, either single-celled or a cluster of cells.
Living eukaryotic organisms belonging to the kingdom fungi. they include mushrooms as well as microbes such as yeast and mold.
An environmentally-sourced sample in which a chemical can be found.
A man-made product or sample in which a chemical can be found.
A mean by which a chemical agent comes in contact with an organism, either under intended or unintended circumstances.
Chemical exposure via the alimentary canal (mouth to anus).
Chemical exposure via the a route other than the alimentary canal.
Chemical exposure facilitated by entry through the mouth.
external_source: Lewis' Dictionary of Toxicology by Robert Alan Lewis; p. 490

definition: Chemical exposure by absorption through the lining of the mouth.
Chemical exposure by absorption through the walls of the rectum.
external_source: Lewis' Dictionary of Toxicology by Robert Alan Lewis; p. 490

definition: Chemical exposure by absorption through the stomach and intestines.
external_source: Lewis' Dictionary of Toxicology by Robert Alan Lewis; p. 490

definition: Chemical exposure by absorption through blood vessels under the tongue.
Chemical exposure facilitated by breathing in, followed by absorption via the lungs. this is the major route of terresitral organisms to aerosols, vapors, gases, and volatile particulates.
external_source: Lewis' Dictionary of Toxicology by Robert Alan Lewis; p. 490

definition: Chemical exposure by contact with the dermis or a cuticle or cornified region of the epidermis.
external_source: Lewis' Dictionary of Toxicology by Robert Alan Lewis; p. 490

definition: Chemical exposure via direct introduction into or through the skin.
Chemical exposure via direct introduction into the circulatory system via the artery.
Chemical exposure via direct introduction into the bone marrow.
Chemical exposure via direct introduction into the brain parenchyma.
Chemical exposure via direct introduction into the cerebral ventricular system.
Chemical exposure via direct introduction into the spinal canal.
Chemical exposure by contact with the walls of the vagina.
external_source: Lewis' Dictionary of Toxicology by Robert Alan Lewis; p. 490

definition: Chemical exposure by contact with the exposed surface oft the eye.
external_source: Lewis' Dictionary of Toxicology by Robert Alan Lewis; p. 490

definition: Chemical exposure via direct injection into the eye.
Chemical exposure via direct introduction into the circulatory system.
Chemical exposure via direct introduction into the circulatory system a the vein.
external_source: Lewis' Dictionary of Toxicology by Robert Alan Lewis; p. 490

definition: Chemical exposure via direct administration into a skeletal muscle.
external_source: Lewis' Dictionary of Toxicology by Robert Alan Lewis; p. 490

definition: Chemical exposure via infusion or injection through the peritoneum.
A mix of matter covering the surface of the earth. Its solids consist of minerals and organis matter, and voids between matter grains consist of water and gas.

A mix of fine particles of matter that can be air-borne.В It can originate in any fragments of matter in the environment, incuding soil, volcanic eruptions, pollution, fibers, organic matter from organisms and other sources.
Liquid wastes from communities, which may be a mixture of domestic effluent from homes and liquid waste from industry. (epa).
Water that is collected on the ground or in a stream, river, lake, wetland or ocean. (epa).
Water that collects or flows underground in the small spaces in soil and rock. it might be a source of water for springs and wells and then used for drinking water. (epa).
Waste that contains paper, cardboard, textiles (for example fabric or carpet), timber, food, garden clippings, glass, plastic and other manufactured materials. (epa).

A site that is specially designed to dispose of waste and operates with a licence granted by the environmental protection agency (epa). the epa reviews licences and, with local authorities, monitors landfills around the country for emissions.
Leaves, straw or compost used to cover growing plants to protect them from the wind or cold. (epa).
A chemical substance that is introduced to an organism and does not originate from within theВ organism itself.

A clear, transparent, sometimes faintly yellow and slightly opalescent fluid that is collected from the tissues throughout the body, flows in the lymphatic vessels (through the lymph nodes), and is eventually added to the venous blood circulation. lymph consists of a clear liquid portion, varying numbers of white blood cells (chiefly lymphocytes), and a few red blood cells. (nci).

A liquid tissue with the primary function of transporting oxygen and carbon dioxide (nci). it supplies the tissues with nutrients, removes waste products, and contains various components of the immune system defending the body against infection.
external_source: Foundational Model of Anatomy (FMA), Rosse, C., Mejino, J.L., Jr.: A reference ontology for biomedical informatics: the Foundational Model of Anatomy. J Biomed Inform 36, 478-500 (2003)

definition: A secretion of the esophageal submucosal glands, contains bicarbonate and mucin and helps balancing the ph and protect the esophagus from acidic gastric reflux.
external_source: Ai, Jiye, et al. "Towards a Body Fluids Ontology: A Unified Application Ontology for Basic and Translational Science."В ICBO. 2011.

definition: A soft yellow wax secreted by glands in the ear canal. (nci).
A thick, oily substance produced by the sebaceous glands located in the dermis.
A viscid fluid secreted by the synovial membrane, serving as a lubricant.
Body substance derived from plasma by the elimination of fibrinogen.
external_source: Foundational Model of Anatomy (FMA), Rosse, C., Mejino, J.L., Jr.: A reference ontology for biomedical informatics: the Foundational Model of Anatomy. J Biomed Inform 36, 478-500 (2003)

definition: Body substance in liquid state contained in the lumen of arterial and venous trees, blood capillary and the cardiac chambers; constitutes the liquid phase of blood.
external_source: Foundational Model of Anatomy (FMA), Rosse, C., Mejino, J.L., Jr.: A reference ontology for biomedical informatics: the Foundational Model of Anatomy. J Biomed Inform 36, 478-500 (2003)

definition: Excretion in liquid state processed by the kidney.
external_source: Foundational Model of Anatomy (FMA), Rosse, C., Mejino, J.L., Jr.: A reference ontology for biomedical informatics: the Foundational Model of Anatomy. J Biomed Inform 36, 478-500 (2003)

definition: Fluid composed of waste products, bile acids, salts, cholesterol, and electrolytes. it is secreted by the liver parenchyma and stored in the gallbladder. (nci).
Fluid excreted from the vagina during menstruation, and contains blood, endometrial tissue, cervical mucus and vaginal secretions.
external_source: Ai, Jiye, et al. "Towards a Body Fluids Ontology: A Unified Application Ontology for Basic and Translational Science."В ICBO. 2011.

definition: Fluid in a follicle ( any small spherical group of cells containing a cavity. (nci)), such as an ovarian follicle.
external_source: Ai, Jiye, et al. "Towards a Body Fluids Ontology: A Unified Application Ontology for Basic and Translational Science."В ICBO. 2011.

definition: Fluid in the cellular layers that cover body and organ surfaces.
external_source: Ai, Jiye, et al. "Towards a Body Fluids Ontology: A Unified Application Ontology for Basic and Translational Science."В ICBO. 2011.

definition: Fluid in the soft fibrous tissue surrounding the teeth.
external_source: Ai, Jiye, et al. "Towards a Body Fluids Ontology: A Unified Application Ontology for Basic and Translational Science."В ICBO. 2011.

definition: Fluid in the vas deference duct.
external_source: Ai, Jiye, et al. "Towards a Body Fluids Ontology: A Unified Application Ontology for Basic and Translational Science."В ICBO. 2011.

definition: Fluid made by the pancreas, and contains digestive enzymes such as insulin and pancreatic lipase.
Fluid of the epididymis duct.
external_source: Ai, Jiye, et al. "Towards a Body Fluids Ontology: A Unified Application Ontology for Basic and Translational Science."В ICBO. 2011.

definition: Fluid originating from the epithelial lining of the intestines, adjoining exocrine glands and from organs such as the liver, which empty into the cavity of the intestines. (msh via nci).
Fluid that is abnormally collected in the pleural cavity. (nci).
Fluid within the eye ball.
Fluids surrounding or related to an embryo. (nci).

FluidsВ that originate in serous glands or mixed glands (mucous and serous cells). they fill body cavities and are typically pale yellow and transparent and of aВ benignВ nature. a common trait of serous fluids is their role in assistingВ digestion,В excretion, andВ respiration.
external_source: Ai, Jiye, et al. "Towards a Body Fluids Ontology: A Unified Application Ontology for Basic and Translational Science."В ICBO. 2011.

definition: Ingested food admixed with gastric secretions contained in the stomach.
external_source: Foundational Model of Anatomy (FMA), Rosse, C., Mejino, J.L., Jr.: A reference ontology for biomedical informatics: the Foundational Model of Anatomy. J Biomed Inform 36, 478-500 (2003)

definition: Normal or abnormal secretions from the vagina. mucus produced by the cervical glands is discharged from the vagina naturally, especially during the childbearing years.В  (nci).
Portion of body fluid suspension that consists of spermatozoa and seminal plasma.
external_source: Foundational Model of Anatomy (FMA), Rosse, C., Mejino, J.L., Jr.: A reference ontology for biomedical informatics: the Foundational Model of Anatomy. J Biomed Inform 36, 478-500 (2003)

definition: Portion of secreted substance produced by a mucous gland or goblet cell.
external_source: Foundational Model of Anatomy (FMA), Rosse, C., Mejino, J.L., Jr.: A reference ontology for biomedical informatics: the Foundational Model of Anatomy. J Biomed Inform 36, 478-500 (2003)

definition: Portion of secreted substance produced by the lacrimal gland.
external_source: Foundational Model of Anatomy (FMA), Rosse, C., Mejino, J.L., Jr.: A reference ontology for biomedical informatics: the Foundational Model of Anatomy. J Biomed Inform 36, 478-500 (2003)

definition: Portion of secreted substance produced by the mammary gland.
external_source: Foundational Model of Anatomy (FMA), Rosse, C., Mejino, J.L., Jr.: A reference ontology for biomedical informatics: the Foundational Model of Anatomy. J Biomed Inform 36, 478-500 (2003)

definition: Portion of secreted substance produced prostatic glands, bulbourethral glands or the seminal vesicles.
external_source: Foundational Model of Anatomy (FMA), Rosse, C., Mejino, J.L., Jr.: A reference ontology for biomedical informatics: the Foundational Model of Anatomy. J Biomed Inform 36, 478-500 (2003)

definition: Secretion produced by a sweat gland.
external_source: Foundational Model of Anatomy (FMA), Rosse, C., Mejino, J.L., Jr.: A reference ontology for biomedical informatics: the Foundational Model of Anatomy. J Biomed Inform 36, 478-500 (2003)

definition: The clear colorless transparent jelly that fills the posterior chamber of the eyeball. (nci).
external_source: Ai, Jiye, et al. "Towards a Body Fluids Ontology: A Unified Application Ontology for Basic and Translational Science."В ICBO. 2011.

definition: The digestive secretions of the gastric glands in the stomach, consisting mainly of pepsin, hydrochloric acid, rennin, and mucin.
external_source: Ai, Jiye, et al. "Towards a Body Fluids Ontology: A Unified Application Ontology for Basic and Translational Science."В ICBO. 2011.

definition: The extracellular fluid component found in the spaces between tissues. this excludes plasma and transcellular fluid. (nci).
external_source: Ai, Jiye, et al. "Towards a Body Fluids Ontology: A Unified Application Ontology for Basic and Translational Science."В ICBO. 2011.

definition: The fluid in the rete testis (network of tubules that convey sperm from the seminiferous tubules within the testicles to the efferent ducts (nci)).
external_source: Ai, Jiye, et al. "Towards a Body Fluids Ontology: A Unified Application Ontology for Basic and Translational Science."В ICBO. 2011.

definition: The fluid in the seminiferous tubule (site of germination and maturation of spermatozoa, and the conduit through which the spermatozoa are transported to the rete testis. (nci)).
external_source: Ai, Jiye, et al. "Towards a Body Fluids Ontology: A Unified Application Ontology for Basic and Translational Science."В ICBO. 2011.

definition: The fluid resulting from glomerular filtration in the kidney, further transformed into tubular fluid and continues into the bladder for excretion as urine.
external_source: Ai, Jiye, et al. "Towards a Body Fluids Ontology: A Unified Application Ontology for Basic and Translational Science."В ICBO. 2011.

definition: The fluid that is contained within the brain ventricles, the subarachnoid space and the central canal of the spinal cord. (nci).
external_source: Ai, Jiye, et al. "Towards a Body Fluids Ontology: A Unified Application Ontology for Basic and Translational Science."В ICBO. 2011.

definition: The watery fluid in the mouth made by the salivary glands. saliva moistens food to help digestion and it helps protect the mouth against infections. (nci).
external_source: Ai, Jiye, et al. "Towards a Body Fluids Ontology: A Unified Application Ontology for Basic and Translational Science."В ICBO. 2011.

definition: The watery fluid which is present in the anterior and posterior chambers of the eye. (nci).
external_source: Ai, Jiye, et al. "Towards a Body Fluids Ontology: A Unified Application Ontology for Basic and Translational Science."В ICBO. 2011.

definition: Transudate contained in the osseous labyrinth outside the membranous labyrinth.
external_source: Foundational Model of Anatomy (FMA), Rosse, C., Mejino, J.L., Jr.: A reference ontology for biomedical informatics: the Foundational Model of Anatomy. J Biomed Inform 36, 478-500 (2003)

definition: Transudate contained within the membranous labyrinth.
external_source: Foundational Model of Anatomy (FMA), Rosse, C., Mejino, J.L., Jr.: A reference ontology for biomedical informatics: the Foundational Model of Anatomy. J Biomed Inform 36, 478-500 (2003)

definition: A blood vessel that carries blood away from the heart. (nci).
A blood vessel that carries blood towards the heart. (nci).
A crescent-like structure located adjacent to the testis. it consists of a single highly coiled duct and is divided into 3 regions: caput (head), corpus (body) and cauda (tail). (nci).
A digestive organ in the abdomen that has both endocrine and exocrine functions. (nci).
A duct carrying spermatozoa from the epididymides to the urethra. (nci).
A hollow muscular organ which receives the blood from the veins and pumps it into the arteries. (nci).
A hollow muscular organ within which the fertilized egg implants and the embryo/fetus develops during pregnancy. (nci).
A mammalian male reproductive accessory gland located adjacent to the urinary bladder and proximal to the prostate. (nci).
A passageway in the head and neck that includes the nasopharynx, oropharynx and laryngopharynx. (nci).
A primary lymphoid organ generally located in the mediastinum near the thoracic inlet and/or along lateral aspects of the neck. (nci).
A reproductive system organ that produces and releases either sperm (testis) or eggs (ovary). (nci).
A sac-like organ located adjacent to the liver that stores and concentrates bile produced by the liver. (NCI)
A salivary gland located under the tongue in the floor of the oral cavity. (nci).
A secondary lymphoid tissue in the mucosa of the pharynx. (nci).
A sensory organ that contains auditory and vestibular apparatuses. (nci).
A small endocrine gland extending from the hypothalamus at the base of the brain. (nci).
A small endocrine gland that arises from the central posterior aspect of the diencephalon. (nci).
A small region of the brain composed of multiple nuclei and located underneath the thalamus.
A structure of special sense serving as an organ of the sense of smell and as an entrance to the respiratory tract. (nci).
A thoracic organ that has variable lobation and is the primary respiratory organ of mammals.
A tiny vessel that can be either a blood capillary or a lymphatic capillary. (nci).
A tube-like structure composed of the vas deferens and surrounding tissue layers, that runs from the abdomen to each of the testicles. (nci).
A tubular structure through which the blood circulates in the body. blood vessels constitute a network composed of arteries, arterioles, capillaries, venules, and veins. (nci).
A tubule that carries lymph throughout the body. (nci).
An abdominal organ that has variable lobation which are composed mainly of hepatic lobules. (nci).
An abdominal organ that is part of the hematopoietic and immune systems. it is composed of the white pulp and the red pulp and is surrounded by a capsule. (nci).
An organ composed of grey and white matter that is the center for intelligence and reasoning. it is protected by the bony cranium. (nci).
An organ that constitutes the external surface of the body. it consists of the epidermis, dermis, and skin appendages. (nci).
An organ that produces and secretes hormones (e.g. endocrine gland), saliva or sweat (e.g. exocrine gland). (nci).
Any number of exocrine glands that secrete saliva into the oral cavity. (nci).
Either of the paired male reproductive glands that produce the male germ cells and the male hormones. (nci).
Endocrine gland(s) adjacent to the trachea in mammals that produce thyroxine and other hormones. (nci).
Endocrine gland, usually in close proximity to the thyroid gland, that produces parathyroid hormone. (nci).
Fibromuscular tissue that separates the thoracic from the abdominal cavity. it increases the volume of the thoracic cavity through contractions, thus facilitating respiration. (nci).
One of a pair of major salivary glands located below the floor of the mouth. (nci).
One of the paired female reproductive glands containing the ova or germ cells; the ovary's stroma is a vascular connective tissue containing numbers of ovarian follicles enclosing the ova (nci).
One of two hemispheric projections of variable size situated in the subcutaneous layer over the pectoralis major muscle on either side of the chest. (nci).

Paired exocrine glands located at the base of the penis, positioned posterior and lateral to the urethra, that produce and secrete a clear viscous liquid that lubricates the urethra in preparation for the passage of sperm. (nci).
Secondary lymphoid organ associated with lymphatic vessels and consisting of an outer cortex, inner medulla and sinuses. (nci).
The avillous section of the intestine composed of crypts and extending from the terminal small intestine to the external orifice. (nci).
The cartilaginous structure of the respiratory tract between the pharynx and the trachea. (nci).
The cavity located at the upper end of the alimentary canal, behind the teeth and gums that is bounded on the outside by the lips, above by the hard and soft palates and below by the tongue. (nci).
The distensible sac-like organ that functions as a reservoir of urine, collecting from the kidneys and eliminating via the urethra. (nci).
The endocrine glands adjacent to the kidneys that consist of the outer adrenal cortex and the inner adrenal medulla in mammals (nci).
The erectile tissue in the vulva. it is composed of the corpora cavernosa and the glans clitoris. (nci).
The external, visible part of the female genitalia surrounding the urethral and vaginal opening(s). (nci).
The female genital canal, extending from the uterus to the vulva. (nci).
The fibrocartilaginous tube extending from the larynx to the bronchi. (nci).
The hard bonelike structures in the jaws of vertebrates; primarily used for eating. (nci).
The male organ of urination and copulation. (nci).
The male reproductive accessory gland that produces prostatic fluid and is located adjacent to or around the urethra distal to the urinary bladder in mammals. (nci).
The muscular organ in the mouth used in taste perception and food ingestion. (nci).
The organs of the urinary tract located in the retroperitoneal cavity adjacent to the spine and composed of the renal cortex and the renal medulla. (nci).
The part of the brain that connects the cerebral hemispheres with the spinal cord. it consists of the mesencephalon, pons, and medulla oblongata. (nci).
The portion of the brain comprising the frontal, parietal, temporal, and occipital lobes and extending through the thalamus. (nci).
The portion of the brain that extends from the brainstem through the cerebellar folia. (nci).
The portion of the central nervous system that lies within the vertebral canal and from which the spinal nerves emerge. (nci).
The portion of the digestive tract between the pharynx and stomach. (nci).

The portion of the forebrain that is located between the telencephalon and the brainstem; it is composed of the thalamus, hypothalamus, subthalamus, and epithalamus, which functions to help regulate many activities of the autonomic nervous system. (nci).
The portion of the gastrointestinal tract located between the esophagus and the proximal duodenum. (nci).
The portion of the gastrointestinal tract that includes the small and large intestines.
The portion of the large intestine which extends from the cecum (or small intestine in animals that don't have a cecum) to the rectum. (nci).
The portion of the small intestine between the duodenum and ileum. (nci).
The portion of the small intestine between the jejunum and large intestine.
The portion of the small intestine between the stomach and jejunum. (nci).
The pouch that encloses the testicles. (nci).
The pouch-like portion of the proximal large intestine opening into the colon. (nci).
The salivary gland located adjacent to the ear. (nci).
The sensory organ of vision. (nci).
The terminal portion of the large intestine extending from the terminus of the colon to the anus or anal canal. (nci).
The tissue occupying the spaces of some bones. it consists of blood vessel sinuses and a network of hematopoietic cells. (nci).
The tube that extends from each kidney to the urinary bladder. (nci).
The tube that extends from the urinary bladder to the urethral opening. (nci).
The tube through which eggs pass from an ovary. (nci).
The upper respiratory tract extending from the nares to the pharynx. (nci).
The villous section of the intestine extending from the pylorus to the proximal large intestine. (nci).
Tubular structure in continuation with the trachea, serving as an air passage. (nci).
All the organs in the body of the organism.
A cellular compartment that separates a cellВ interiorВ from its exterior.
A cellular compartment that separates the matrix of subcellularВ organelles from the intermembrane space.
An intracellular non-membrane-bounded organelle comprising a matrix of coalesced lipids surrounded by a phospholipid monolayer. may include associated proteins.В source:В goc:tb,goc:mah.
Either of the lipid bilayers that surround the mitochondrion and form the mitochondrial envelope.В source:В nif subcellular:sao1045389829,В goc:mah.
Intracellular membrane.
The inner, i.e. lumen-facing, lipid bilayer of the mitochondrial envelope. it is highly folded to form cristae.В source:В goc:ai.

An endocytic patch  that consists of an actin-containing structure found at the plasma membrane in cells; formed of networks of branched actin filaments that lie just beneath the plasma membrane and assemble, move, and disassemble rapidly. An example of this is the actin cortical patch found in Saccharomyces cerevisiae. (Gene Ontology).
A cell junction at which anchoring proteins (cadherins or integrins) extend through the plasma membrane and are attached to actin filaments. (Gene Ontology).
The region of the plasma membrane located at the apical end of the cell. (Gene Ontology).
The lipid bilayer surrounding an autophagosome, a double-membrane-bounded vesicle in which endogenous cellular material is sequestered. (Gene Ontology).

A layer of phospholipids and protein found on neuronal axons. this structure acts as an electrical insulator that allows nerve impulses to travel faster by increasing the resistance and decreasing the capacitance over that found in unmyelinated nerve fibers. (nci).
A projection of a neuron that conducts electrical impulses away from the neuronal cell body.

A thin layer of dense material found in various animal tissues interposed between the cells and the adjacent connective tissue. It consists of the basal lamina plus an associated layer of reticulin fibers. (Gene Ontology).

A class of nuclear body, first seen after silver staining by Ramon y Cajal in 1903, enriched in small nuclear ribonucleoproteins, and certain general RNA polymerase II transcription factors; ultrastructurally, they appear as a tangle of coiled, electron-dense threads roughly 0.5 micrometers in diameter; involved in aspects of snRNP biogenesis; the protein coilin serves as a marker for Cajal bodies. Some argue that Cajal bodies are the sites for preassembly of transcriptosomes, unitary particles involved in transcription and processing of RNA. (Gene Ontology).

A membrane raft that forms small pit, depression, or invagination that communicates with the outside of a cell and extends inward, indenting the cytoplasm and the cell membrane. Examples include flask-shaped invaginations of the plasma membrane in adipocytes associated with caveolin proteins, and minute pits or incuppings of the cell membrane formed during pinocytosis.  Caveolae may be pinched off to form free vesicles within the cytoplasm. (Gene Ontology).

An envelope that surrounds a bacterial cell and includes the cytoplasmic membrane and everything external, encompassing the periplasmic space, cell wall, and outer membrane if present. (Gene Ontology).

A cellular component that forms a specialized region of connection between two or more cells or between a cell and the extracellular matrix. At a cell junction, anchoring proteins extend through the plasma membrane to link cytoskeletal proteins in one cell to cytoskeletal proteins in neighboring cells or to proteins in the extracellular matrix. (Gene Ontology).
A prolongation or process extending from a cell, e.g. a flagellum or axon. (Gene Ontology).
The external part of the cell wall and/or plasma membrane. (Gene Ontology).

A cellular organelle, found close to the nucleus in many eukaryotic cells, consisting of a small cylinder with microtubular walls, 300-500 nm long and 150-250 nm in diameter. It contains nine short, parallel, peripheral microtubular fibrils, each fibril consisting of one complete microtubule fused to two incomplete microtubules. Cells usually have two centrioles, lying at right angles to each other. At division, each pair of centrioles generates another pair and the twin pairs form the pole of the mitotic spindle. (Gene Ontology).

OBSOLETE. The region of a eukaryotic chromosome that is attached to the spindle during nuclear division. It is defined genetically as the region of the chromosome that always segregates at the first division of meiosis; the region of the chromosome in which no crossing over occurs. At the start of M phase, each chromosome consists of two sister chromatids with a constriction at a point which forms the centromere. During late prophase two kinetochores assemble on each centromere, one kinetochore on each sister chromatid. (Gene Ontology).

A structure comprised of a core structure (in most organisms, a pair of centrioles) and peripheral material from which a microtubule-based structure, such as a spindle apparatus, is organized. Centrosomes occur close to the nucleus during interphase in many eukaryotic cells, though in animal cells it changes continually during the cell-division cycle. (Gene Ontology).
The volume enclosed by the membrane of a chromaffin granule. (Gene Ontology).

The lipid bilayer surrounding a chromaffin granule, a specialized secretory vesicle found in the cells of adrenal glands and various other organs, which is concerned with the synthesis, storage, metabolism, and secretion of epinephrine and norepinephrine. (Gene Ontology).
A structure composed of a very long molecule of DNA and associated proteins (e.g. histones) that carries hereditary information. (Gene Ontology).

A specialized eukaryotic organelle that consists of a filiform extrusion of the cell surface and of some cytoplasmic parts. Each cilium is largely bounded by an extrusion of the cytoplasmic (plasma) membrane, and contains a regular longitudinal array of microtubules, anchored to a basal body. (Gene Ontology).
The bundle of microtubules and associated proteins that forms the core of cilia (also called flagella) in eukaryotic cells and is responsible for their movements. (Gene Ontology).

A membrane-tethered, short cylindrical array of microtubules and associated proteins found at the base of a eukaryotic cilium (also called flagellum) that is similar in structure to a centriole and derives from it. The cilium basal body is the site of assembly and remodelling of the cilium and serves as a nucleation site for axoneme growth. As well as anchoring the cilium, it is thought to provide a selective gateway regulating the entry of ciliary proteins and vesicles by intraflagellar transport. (Gene Ontology).
The network of interconnected tubular and cisternal structures located at the convex side of the Golgi apparatus, which abuts the endoplasmic reticulum. (Gene Ontology).

A part of the endomembrane system in the form of an invagination of a membrane upon which a clathrin coat forms, and that can be converted by vesicle budding into a clathrin-coated vesicle. Coated pits form on the plasma membrane, where they are involved in receptor-mediated selective transport of many proteins and other macromolecules across the cell membrane, in the trans-Golgi network, and on some endosomes. (Gene Ontology).
The cleavage furrow is a plasma membrane invagination at the cell division site. The cleavage furrow begins as a shallow groove and eventually deepens to divide the cytoplasm. (Gene Ontology).
The portion of the cell contained within the plasma membrane but excluding the nucleus.
A dense aggregation in the cytosol composed of proteins and RNAs that appear when the cell is under stress. (Gene Ontology).
A vesicle found in the cytoplasm of a cell. (Gene Ontology).
The volume enclosed by a cytoplasmic vesicle. (Gene Ontology).
The lipid bilayer surrounding a cytoplasmic vesicle. (Gene Ontology).

Any of the various filamentous elements that form the internal framework of cells, and typically remain after treatment of the cells with mild detergent to remove membrane constituents and soluble components of the cytoplasm. The term embraces intermediate filaments, microfilaments, microtubules, the microtrabecular lattice, and other structures characterized by a polymeric filamentous nature and long-range order within the cell. The various elements of the cytoskeleton not only serve in the maintenance of cellular shape but also have roles in other cellular functions, including cellular movement, cell division, endocytosis, and movement of organelles. (Gene Ontology).
The part of the cytoplasm that does not contain organelles but which does contain other particulate matter, such as protein complexes

A small, membranous protrusion from a dendrite that forms a postsynaptic compartment - typically receiving input from a single presynapse.  They function as partially isolated biochemical and an electrical compartments. Spine morphology is variable including "thin", "stubby", "mushroom", and "branched", with a continuum of intermediate morphologies. They typically terminate in a bulb shape, linked to the dendritic shaft by a restriction. Spine remodeling is though to be involved in synaptic plasticity. (Gene Ontology).

A membrane-bounded organelle that receives incoming material from primary endocytic vesicles that have been generated by clathrin-dependent and clathrin-independent endocytosis; vesicles fuse with the early endosome to deliver cargo for sorting into recycling or degradation pathways. (Gene Ontology).
The lipid bilayer surrounding an early endosome. (Gene Ontology).

A collection of membranous structures involved in transport within the cell. The main components of the endomembrane system are endoplasmic reticulum, Golgi bodies, vesicles, cell membrane and nuclear envelope. Members of the endomembrane system pass materials through each other or though the use of vesicles. (Gene Ontology).

A network of tubular membranes within the cytoplasm of the cell, occurring either with a smooth surface (smooth endoplasmic reticulum) or studded with ribosomes (rough endoplasmic reticulum), involved in the transport of materials. (Infoplease Dictionary via NCI)
The volume enclosed by the membranes of the host cell endoplasmic reticulum. (Gene Ontology).
The lipid bilayer surrounding the host cell endoplasmic reticulum. (Gene Ontology).

A complex system of membrane-bounded compartments located between endoplasmic reticulum (ER) and the Golgi complex, with a distinctive membrane protein composition; involved in ER-to-Golgi  and Golgi-to-ER transport. (Gene Ontology).
A membrane bound cytoplasmic compartment that drives molecular traffic between the plasma membrane and lysosome.
A lipid bilayer enclosing an endosomal compartment.
The space external to the outermost structure of a cell.

A network of fibers that hold cells together. It is found within the extracellular space and in association with the basement membrane of the cell surface. It promotes cellular proliferation and provides a supporting structure to which cells or cell lysates in culture dishes adhere. It is broken down during normal physiological and disease processes such as bone remodeling, embryogenesis, cancer, and arthritis. (NCI Thesaurus)
Part of a multicellular organism outside the cells proper, usually taken to be outside the plasma membranes, and occupied by fluid.

Thin, stiff, actin-based protrusion extended by the leading edge of a motile cell such as a crawling fibroblast or amoeba, or an axonal or dendritic growth cone, or a dendritic shaft. (Gene Ontology).

Long whiplike or feathery structures borne either singly or in groups by the motile cells of many bacteria and unicellular eukaryotes and by the motile male gametes of many eukaryotic organisms, which propel the cell through a liquid medium. (Gene Ontology, OBSOLETE).
Small region on the surface of a cell that anchors the cell to the extracellular matrix and that forms a point of termination of actin filaments. (Gene Ontology).

Gems are nuclear bodies, often found paired or juxtaposed to Cajal bodies, called gems for "gemini of CBs". It is not clear if Cajal bodes and gems are distinct nuclear bodies or if they should be considered as two manifestations of the same structure. (Uniprot).

A compound membranous cytoplasmic organelle of eukaryotic cells, consisting of flattened, ribosome-free vesicles arranged in a more or less regular stack. Note that the Golgi apparatus can be located in various places in the cytoplasm.
The volume enclosed by the membranes of any cisterna or subcompartment of the Golgi apparatus, including the cis- and trans-Golgi networks. (Gene Ontology).
The lipid bilayer surrounding any of the compartments of the Golgi apparatus. (Gene Ontology).
A multisubunit complex that is located at the centromeric region of DNA and provides an attachment point for the spindle microtubules. (Gene Ontology).
A thin sheetlike process extended by the leading edge of a migrating cell or extending cell process; contains a dense meshwork of actin filaments. (Gene Ontology).
The portion of the plasma membrane surrounding a lamellipodium. (Gene Ontology).

A prelysosomal endocytic organelle differentiated from early endosomes by lower lumenal pH and different protein composition. Late endosomes are more spherical than early endosomes and are mostly juxtanuclear, being concentrated near the microtubule organizing center. (Gene Ontology).
The lipid bilayer surrounding a late endosome. (Gene Ontology).
В A sac-like compartment inside a cell that has enzymes that can break down cellular components that need to be destroyed. (NCI).
The area within the membrane of a lysosome. (NCI).
A lipid bilayer that encloses a lysosome. (NCI)
A tissue-specific, membrane-bounded cytoplasmic organelle within which melanin pigments are synthesized and stored. Melanosomes are synthesized in melanocyte cells. (Gene Ontology).
The lipid bilayer surrounding a melanosome. (Gene Ontology).

Any of the small (10-200 nm), heterogeneous, highly dynamic, sterol- and sphingolipid-enriched membrane domains that compartmentalize cellular processes. Small rafts can sometimes be stabilized to form larger platforms through protein-protein and protein-lipid interactions. (Gene Ontology).

Any of the small, heterogeneous, artifactual, vesicular particles, 50-150 nm in diameter, that are formed when some eukaryotic cells are homogenized and that sediment on centrifugation at 100000 g. (Gene Ontology, OBSOLETE).
The membrane surrounding the microsome. (Uniprot).
The portion of the plasma membrane surrounding a microvillus. (Gene Ontology).

A thin cytoplasmic bridge formed between daughter cells at the end of cytokinesis. The midbody forms where the contractile ring constricts, and may persist for some time before finally breaking to complete cytokinesis. (Gene Ontology).
The region between the inner and outer lipid bilayers of the mitochondrial envelope. (Gene Ontology).

The gel-like material, with considerable fine structure, that lies in the matrix space, or lumen, of a mitochondrion. It contains the enzymes of the tricarboxylic acid cycle and, in some organisms, the enzymes concerned with fatty acid oxidation. (Gene Ontology).
The region of a mitochondrion to which the DNA is confined. (Gene Ontology).
The outer, i.e. cytoplasm-facing, lipid bilayer of the mitochondrial envelope. (Gene Ontology).

A type of endosome in which regions of the limiting endosomal membrane invaginate to form internal vesicles; membrane proteins that enter the internal vesicles are sequestered from the cytoplasm. (Gene Ontology).

The contractile element of skeletal and cardiac muscle cells; a long, highly organized bundle of actin, myosin, and other proteins that constructs a myocyte and contracts by a sliding filament mechanism.

The double lipid bilayer enclosing the nucleus and separating its contents from the rest of the cytoplasm; includes the intermembrane space, a gap of width 20-40 nm (also called the perinuclear space). (Gene Ontology).
Any of the numerous similar discrete openings in the nuclear envelope of a eukaryotic cell, where the inner and outer nuclear membranes are joined. (Gene Ontology).

A small, dense body one or more of which are present in the nucleus of eukaryotic cells. It is rich in RNA and protein, is not bounded by a limiting membrane, and is not seen during mitosis. Its prime function is the transcription of the nucleolar DNA into 45S ribosomal-precursor RNA, the processing of this RNA into 5.8S, 18S, and 28S components of ribosomal RNA, and the association of these components with 5S RNA and proteins synthesized outside the nucleolus. This association results in the formation of ribonucleoprotein precursors; these pass into the cytoplasm and mature into the 40S and 60S subunits of the ribosome. (Gene Ontology).
That part of the nuclear content other than the chromosomes or the nucleolus. (Gene Ontology).
A body within the cell, surrounded by a membrane, within which lie the chromosomes, one or more nucleoli, combined with proteins, and exhibits mitosis. (NCI)

The double lipid bilayer enclosing the nucleus and separating its contents from the rest of the cytoplasm; includes the intermembrane space, a gap of width 20-40 nm (also called the perinuclear space). (Gene Ontology).
The dense fibrillar network lying on the inner side of the nuclear membrane. (Gene Ontology).
Either of the lipid bilayers that surround the nucleus and form the nuclear envelope; excludes the intermembrane space. (Gene Ontology).
The outer, i.e. cytoplasm-facing, lipid bilayer of the nuclear envelope; continuous with the endoplasmic reticulum of the cell and sometimes studded with ribosomes. (Gene Ontology).
A discrete extra-nucleolar subnuclear domain, 20-50 in number, in which splicing factors are seen to be localized by immunofluorescence microscopy. (Gene Ontology).
The external membrane of Gram-negative bacteria or certain organelles such as mitochondria and chloroplasts; freely permeable to most ions and metabolites. (Gene Ontology).

A focus in the cytoplasm where mRNAs may become inactivated by decapping or some other mechanism. Protein and RNA localized to these foci are involved in mRNA degradation, nonsense-mediated mRNA decay (NMD), translational repression, and RNA-mediated gene silencing. (Gene Ontology).
Cytoplasm situated near, or occurring around, the nucleus. (Gene Ontology).
The region between the inner (cytoplasmic) and outer membrane (Gram-negative Bacteria) or cytoplasmic membrane and cell wall (Fungi and Gram-positive Bacteria). (Gene Ontology).

A small organelle enclosed by a single membrane, and found in most eukaryotic cells. Contains peroxidases and other enzymes involved in a variety of metabolic processes including free radical detoxification, lipid catabolism and biosynthesis, and hydrogen peroxide metabolism. (Gene Ontology).
The volume contained within the membranes of a peroxisome; in many cells the matrix contains a crystalloid core largely composed of urate oxidase. (Gene Ontology).
The lipid bilayer surrounding a peroxisome. (Gene Ontology).
The lipid bilayer surrounding a phagocytic vesicle. (Gene Ontology).
The inner segment of a vertebrate photoreceptor containing mitochondria, ribosomes and membranes where opsin molecules are assembled and passed to be part of the outer segment discs. (Gene Ontology).
The outer segment of a vertebrate photoreceptor that contains discs of photoreceptive membranes. (Gene Ontology).

A class of nuclear body; they react against SP100 auto-antibodies (PML, promyelocytic leukemia); cells typically contain 10-30 PML bodies per nucleus; alterations in the localization of PML bodies occurs after viral infection. (Gene Ontology).

An actin-rich adhesion structure characterized by formation upon cell substrate contact and localization at the substrate-attached part of the cell, contain an F-actin-rich core surrounded by a ring structure containing proteins such as vinculin and talin, and have a diameter of 0.5 mm. (Gene Ontology).

A specialized area of membrane facing the presynaptic membrane on the tip of the nerve ending and separated from it by a minute cleft (the synaptic cleft). Neurotransmitters cross the synaptic cleft and transmit the signal to the postsynaptic membrane. (Gene Ontology).

An electron dense network of proteins within and adjacent to the postsynaptic membrane of an asymetric, neuron-neuron synapse. Its major components include neurotransmitter receptors and the proteins that spatially and functionally organize them such as anchoring and scaffolding molecules, signaling enzymes and cytoskeletal components. (Gene Ontology).

A specialized area of membrane of the axon terminal that faces the plasma membrane of the neuron or muscle fiber with which the axon terminal establishes a synaptic junction; many synaptic junctions exhibit structural presynaptic characteristics, such as conical, electron-dense internal protrusions, that distinguish it from the remainder of the axon plasma membrane. (Gene Ontology).
The membrane surrounding the prevacuolar compartment. (Uniprot).
The lipid bilayer surrounding a recycling endosome. (Gene Ontology).

The rough (or granular) endoplasmic reticulum (ER) has ribosomes adhering to the outer surface; the ribosomes are the site of translation of the mRNA for those proteins which are either to be retained within the cisternae (ER-resident proteins), the proteins of the lysosomes, or the proteins destined for export from the cell. Glycoproteins undergo their initial glycosylation within the cisternae. (Gene Ontology).
The lipid bilayer surrounding the rough endoplasmic reticulum. (Gene Ontology).
Projection at the leading edge of a crawling cell; the protrusions are supported by a microfilament meshwork. (Gene Ontology).
The portion of the plasma membrane surrounding a ruffle. (Gene Ontology).

The outer membrane of a muscle cell, consisting of the plasma membrane, a covering basement membrane (about 100 nm thick and sometimes common to more than one fiber), and the associated loose network of collagen fibers. (Gene Ontology).
The repeating unit of a myofibril in a muscle cell, composed of an array of overlapping thick and thin filaments between two adjacent Z discs. (Gene Ontology).
The lipid bilayer surrounding the sarcoplasmic reticulum. (Gene Ontology).
A cytoplasmic, membrane bound vesicle that is capable of fusing to the plasma membrane to release its contents into the extracellular space. (Gene Ontology).
The secretory vesicle compartment bounded by the membrane of the secretory vesicle. (Uniprot).
The membrane of a secretory vesicle.

The array of microtubules and associated molecules that forms between opposite poles of a eukaryotic cell during mitosis or meiosis and serves to move the duplicated chromosomes apart. (Gene Ontology).

Either of the ends of a spindle, where spindle microtubules are organized; usually contains a microtubule organizing center and accessory molecules, spindle microtubules and astral microtubules. (Gene Ontology).

An actin-based protrusion from the apical surface of auditory and vestibular hair cells and of neuromast cells. These protrusions are supported by a bundle of cross-linked actin filaments (an actin cable), oriented such that the plus (barbed) ends are at the tip of the protrusion, capped by a tip complex which bridges to the plasma. Bundles of stereocilia act as mechanosensory organelles. (Gene Ontology).

The junction between a nerve fiber of one neuron and another neuron, muscle fiber or glial cell. As the nerve fiber approaches the synapse it enlarges into a specialized structure, the presynaptic nerve ending, which contains mitochondria and synaptic vesicles. At the tip of the nerve ending is the presynaptic membrane; facing it, and separated from it by a minute cleft (the synaptic cleft) is a specialized area of membrane on the receiving cell, known as the postsynaptic membrane. In response to the arrival of nerve impulses, the presynaptic nerve ending secretes molecules of neurotransmitters into the synaptic cleft. These diffuse across the cleft and transmit the signal to the postsynaptic membrane. (Gene Ontology).
The lipid bilayer surrounding a synaptic vesicle. (Gene Ontology).

Any of the discrete particles (nerve-ending particles) formed from the clublike presynaptic nerve endings that resist disruption and are snapped or torn off their attachments when brain tissue is homogenized in media isosmotic to plasma. (Gene Ontology, OBSOLETE).

A complex of DNA and protein that seals the end of a chromosome. The telomeric DNA consists of simple tandemly repeated sequences specific for each species. Typically one strand is G-rich and the other C-rich. The G-rich strand forms a 3'-terminal overhang, the length of which varies with species. The single strand overhang is bound by a variety of proteins, including telomere capping proteins that bind to the single-stranded DNA. (Gene Ontology, OBSOLETE).

An occluding cell-cell junction that is composed of a branching network of sealing strands that completely encircles the apical end of each cell in an epithelial sheet; the outer leaflets of the two interacting plasma membranes are seen to be tightly apposed where sealing strands are present. Each sealing strand is composed of a long row of transmembrane adhesion proteins embedded in each of the two interacting plasma membranes. (Gene Ontology).

The network of interconnected tubular and cisternal structures located within the Golgi apparatus on the side distal to the endoplasmic reticulum, from which secretory vesicles emerge. The trans-Golgi network is important in the later stages of protein secretion where it is thought to play a key role in the sorting and targeting of secreted proteins to the correct destination. (Gene Ontology).
The lipid bilayer surrounding any of the compartments that make up the trans-Golgi network. (Gene Ontology).

A closed structure, found only in eukaryotic cells, that is completely surrounded by unit membrane and contains liquid material. Cells contain one or several vacuoles, that may have different functions from each other. Vacuoles have a diverse array of functions. They can act as a storage organelle for nutrients or waste products, as a degradative compartment, as a cost-effective way of increasing cell size, and as a homeostatic regulator controlling both turgor pressure and pH of the cytosol. (Gene Ontology).
The lipid bilayer surrounding the vacuole and separating its contents from the cytoplasm of the cell. (Gene Ontology).
В the system of muscles, tendons, ligaments, bones, joints and associated tissues that move the body and maintain its form.
В the system that contains the heart and the blood vessels and moves blood throughout the body.
A system of glands and cells that make hormones that are released directly into the blood and travel to tissues and organs all over the body.
A system of glands that secrete fluids delivered via ducts and tubes directly to organs including the skin. examples include the exocrine pancreas and the prostate gland.

The bodily system of organs and tissues, primarily the bone marrow, spleen, tonsils, and lymph nodes, involved in the production of blood considered together with the interconnected system of spaces and vessels between body tissues and organs by which lymph circulates throughout the body.

The complex group of organs like thymus, spleen, tonsils, lymphatic system, hematopoetic system and cells like lymphocytes, granulocytes, monocytes and macrophages that defends the body against infection or disease.

The enveloping membrane of the body; includes, in addition to the epidermis and dermis, all of the derivatives of the epidermis, e.g., hairs, nails, sudoriferous and sebaceous glands, and mammary glands.

The organized network of nerve tissue in the body. it includes the central nervous system (the brain and spinal cord), the peripheral nervous system (nerves that extend from the spinal cord to the rest of the body), and other nerve tissue.
The organs and tissues involved in the production and maturation of gametes and in their union and subsequent development as offspring.
The organs of the body that produce and discharge urine. these include the kidneys, ureters, bladder, and urethra.
The organs that are involved in breathing. these include the nose, throat, larynx, trachea, bronchi, and lungs.
The system that includes the esophagus, stomach, small and large intestine, anus, liver, biliary tract, and pancreas.
В involuntary muscle tissue of the internal organs. it is composed of elongated muscle cells or fibers that are not arranged in a striated pattern and form layers of muscle tissue. (nci).
В the supporting or framework tissue of the animal body, formed of fibrous and ground substance with more or less numerous cells of various kinds (nci).
A band of fibrous connective tissue that joins bone to muscle. (nci).
A bundle of neuronal fibers that transmits electrochemical impulses encoding sensory and motor information from one body part to another. (nci).
A cluster of nervous tissue principally composed of neuronal cell bodies external to the central nervous system (cns). (nci).
A dense connective tissue sheath surrounding a bundle of muscle fibers. (nci).
A fibrous soft tissue with the ability to contract to produce force and motion. (nci).
A specialized form of connective tissue consisting primarily of adipocytes (fat cells), surrounded by a meshwork of collagen fibers. (NCI)
A structural protein and connective tissue component in fiber form composed of numerous fine fibrils, which provides strength and flexibility to tissue. (nci).
A type of connective tissue composed of chondrocytes and an extracellular matrix, composed of collagen, elastin, and ground substance. (nci).
A type of connective tissue consisting of an outer mantel of microfibrils and an amorphous elastin inner core capable of repetitive cycles of extension and recoil. (nci).
Adipose tissue located under the dermis. it binds underlying structures with the skin. (nci).

An organ present in some vertebrates during embryonic gestation that surrounds the fetus and provides it with nutrients and oxygen, facilitates gas and waste exchange between the fetus and mother, and provides parasitic cloaking from the mother's immune system by excretion of neurokinin b. (nci).
Band of fibrous tissue connecting bone to bone or cartilage to bone thereby supporting or strengthening a joint. (nci).
Connective tissue in which the fibrous component predominates. the cells, ground substance, and tissue fluid represent a minor component.
Connective tissue that forms the skeletal components of the body. (nci).
Epithelium composed of a single layer of cells attached to a basement membrane. (nci).
Epithelium which consists of more than one layer of epithelial cells that may or may not be in contact with a basement membrane. (uwda via nci).
Irregular connective tissue, the intercellular matrix of which contains a sparse irregular network of collagen and elastic fiber bundles. (nci).
Proteinaceous fibrils found in connective tissue that are comprised of type iii collagen and form a mesh that can support soft tissue structure. (nci).
Striated muscles that are under voluntary control of the organism. they are connected at either or both ends to a bone and are utilized for locomotion and other movements. (nci).
The connection point between two bones or skeletal elements. the joint may be fixed or movable. (nci).
The cutaneous plate on the dorsal surface of the distal end of a finger or toe. (nci).

The epithelial portion of the skin (cutis). it consists of the following layers: stratum corneum (horny layer), stratum granulosum (granular layer), stratum spinosum (prickle cell layer), and stratum basale (basal cell layer). (nci).
The filamentous outgrowth of the epidermis. (nci).
The inner layer of the two main layers of the skin. The dermis has connective tissue, blood vessels, oil and sweat glands, nerves, hair follicles, and other structures.В  (NCI)

The nerve tissue composed of nerve cell bodies, unmyelinated nerve fibers and supportive tissue found in the brain and spinal cord. it is differentiated from the white matter by color of the tissues and the presence of more myelinated nerve cells in the white matter. (nci).
The nerve tissue forming the bulk of the deep parts of the brain and the superficial parts of the spinal cord. (nci).
The striated muscle tissue of the heart enveloped by the epicardium and the endocardium.
The supporting or framework tissue of the animal body, formed of fibrous and ground substance with more or less numerous cells of various kinds. (nci).
The tissue that generates and conducts electrical signals in the body. it contains the neurons. (nci).
Type of tissue that serves primarily as a covering or lining of body parts, protecting the body; it also functions in absorption, transport, and secretion.
All tissues in the body of the organism.
One of the five basic tastes.
One of the five basic tastes.
One of the five basic tastes.
One of the five basic tastes.
Dry, puckeringВ mouthfeelВ caused byВ tannins.
One of the five basic tastes, trigerred by chemical reaction on receptors for glutamate.
A silky consistency which is devoided of grainy rough texture, and often described as "melts in your mouth".

a deficiency in this enzyme results in accumulation of n-acetyl-l-aspartic acid in plasma, spinal fluid, and urine. symptoms, which present at birth, include myclonus, irritability, hypotonia, motor retardation, and poor head control.

A adolescence-adult electroclinical syndrome that is characterized by brief, involuntary twitching of a muscle or a group of muscles (myoclonus) early in the morning with onset between 12 and 18 years. (do).

A basal ganglia disease characterized by progressive neuronal loss predominantly involving the frontal and/or temporal lobes of the brain resulting in a gradual and progressive decline in behavior or language. (do).
A bile duct adenocarcinoma that has material basis in bile duct epithelial cells. (do).
A blood platelet disease that is characterized by the presence of high platelet counts in the blood. (do).

definition: A bone deterioration disease that has material basis in bony spurs, disc degeneration, or thickened ligaments which results in narrowing located in spinal cord. (do).
A bone deterioration disease that has material basis in gradual dehydration and tears located in intervertebral disc. (do).

A bone remodeling disease that has material basis in impaired mineralization or calcification of bones before epiphyseal closure due to deficiency or impaired metabolism of vitamin d, phosphorus or calcium which results in softening and deformity located in bone. (do).
A brain disease that is caused by damage to the motor control centers of the developing brain during pregnancy, during childbirth or after birth, which affects muscle movement and balance. (do).

definition: A brain disease that is characterised by the presence of neurological symptoms of ophthalmoplegia, ataxia, and confusion caused by biochemical lesions of the central nervous system after exhaustion of b-vitamin reserves, in particular thiamine (vitamin b1). (do).

A brain disease that is characterized by loss of brain function, the occurrence of confusion, altered level of consciousness, and coma that results when the liver is unable to remove toxins from the blood. (do).
A brain disease that is characterized by moderate to severe headaches, nausea, extreme sensitivity to light and sound and intense unilaterial throbbing or pulsing. (do).

A brain disease that is characterized by the occurrance of at least two unprovoked seizures resulting from a persistent epileptogenic abnormality of the brain that is able to spontaneously generate paroxysmal activity and typically manifested by sudden brief episodes of altered or diminished consciousness, involuntary movements, or convulsions. (do).
A breast cancer that has material basis in abnormally proliferating cells derives from epithelial cells. (do).

definition: A bronchial disease that is characterized by chronic inflammation and narrowing of the airways, which is caused by a combination of environmental and genetic factors. the disease has symptom recurring periods of wheezing (a whistling sound while breathing), has symptom chest tightness, has symptom shortness of breath, has symptom mucus production and has symptom coughing. the symptoms appear due to a variety of triggers such as allergens, irritants, respiratory infections, weather changes, exercise, stress, reflux disease, medications, foods and emotional anxiety. (do).
A cancer that affects the blood or bone marrow characterized by an abnormal proliferation of blood cells. (do).
A carcinoma that derives from squamous epithelial cells. (do).
A carcinoma that has material basis in abnormally proliferating cells, derives from epithelial cells, which originate in glandular tissue. (do).
A cardiovascular system disease that involves the heart. (do).
A cardiovascular system disease that primarily affects the blood vessels which includes the arteries, veins and capillaries that carry blood to and from the heart. (do).
A cell type benign neoplam that is composed of epithelial tissue on papillae of vascularized connective tissue. (do).

definition: A cell type cancer that has material basis in abnormally proliferating cells derives from embryonic mesoderm. (do).
A cell type cancer that has material basis in abnormally proliferating cells derives from melanocytes which are found in skin, the bowel and the eye. (do).
A central nervous system cancer that are manifested in the central nervous system and arise from the arachnoid cap cells of the arachnoid villi in the meninges. (do).
A central nervous system disease that results in the progressive deterioration of function or structure of neurons. (do).
A cerebellar disease characterized by ataxia originating in the cerebellum. (do).
A cessation of life occuring during childhood. (nci ctcae).

definition: A cessation of life. (nci ctcae).
A cholestasis characterized by blockage of the ducts that carry bile from the liver to the gallbladder. (do).
A ciliopathy that is characterized by impaired function of the cilia lining the respiratory tract (lower and upper, sinuses, eustachian tube, middle ear) and fallopian tube. (do).
A cognitive disorder resulting from a loss of brain function affecting memory, thinking, language, judgement and behavior. (do).

A collagen disease that is considered an overlap of three diseases, systemic lupus erythematosus, scleroderma, and polymyositis with very high titers of circulating antinuclear antibody to a ribonucleoprotein antigen. (do).
A colorectal cancer that is located in the colon. (do).

definition: this enzyme is required for purine degradation. specifically, it catalyzes the conversion of inosine and guanosine to hypoxanthine.

A connective tissue cancer that has material basis in fibrous connective tissue and characterized by the presence of immature proliferating fibroblasts or undifferentiated anaplastic spindle cells in a storiform pattern. (do).

definition: A connective tissue cancer that is located in bone and is characterized by uncontrolled cellular proliferation that destroys normal bone tissue. (do).
