An endogenous depression that is characterized by an all-encompassing low mood accompanied by low self-esteem, and by loss of interest or pleasure in normally enjoyable activities. (do).
An esophagitis characterized by inflammation involving eosinophils located in esophagus. (do).
An eye disease that is characterized by elevated intraocular pressure in the absence of optic nerve damage or visual field loss. (do).

An inherited metabolic disorder characterized by reduced production of serotonin and dopamine resulting in hypotonia, hypokinesia, ptosis oculogyric crises, and signs of autonomic dysfunction with onset in infancy or childhood that has material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the ddc gene on chromosome 7p12. (do).

An inherited metabolic disorder characterized by the bodys inability to break down proteins and fats to produce energy. it is a disorder of fatty acid, amino acid, and choline metabolism and has an autosomal recessive inheritance pattern. it has material basis in mutations in the etfa, etfb and etfdh genes. it presents three clinical phenotypes: a neonatal-onset form with congenital anomalies (type i), a neonatal-onset form without congenital anomalies (type ii), and a late-onset form (type iii). the neonatal-onset forms are usually fatal. (do).
a deficiency in this enzyme results in accumulation of glycerol in urine and serum. symptoms include cryptorchism, trabismus, myopathy, lethargy, and vomiting.
An inherited metabolic disorder that involves certain enzymes in the heme bio-synthetic pathway resulting in the overproduction and accumulation of the porphyrins. (do).
An interstitial lung disease that is caused by the inhalation of dust. (do).
An intestinal disease characterized by inflammation located in all parts of digestive tract. (do).

An intestinal disease that is characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance of unrestricted intestinal absorption of both cholesterol and plant-derived cholesterol-like molecules resulting in xanthomas, arthralgia, premature atherosclerosis, and hemolytic anemia with stomatocytosis and macrothrombocytopenia that has material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the abcg8 gene or in the abcg5 gene, both of which are located on chromosome 2p21. (do).

it is classified as an organic acid disorder, which is a condition that leads to an abnormal buildup of particular acids known as organic acids. abnormal levels of organic acids in the blood (organic acidemia), urine (organic aciduria), and tissues can be toxic and can cause serious health problems.

propionyl-coa carboxylase (pcc), comprised of alpha and beta subunits, catalyzes the first step in the catabolism of propionyl-coa, an important intermediate in the metabolism of several amino acids. a mutation in this enzyme causes accumulation of ammonia and propionylcarnitine (c3) in the blood; carnitine , glutamine, glycine, and propionic acid in the plasma; 3-hydroxypropionic acid, 3-hydroxyvaleric acid, 5-oxoproline, acylcarnitin, glycine, methylcitric acid, propionylglycine and tiglylcine in the urine.
An organic acidemia that involves an accumulation of methylmalonic acid in the blood. (do).

the disease is characterized in an infant by the presence of sweet-smelling urine, with an odor similar to that of maple syrup. increased amounts of valine, leucine and isoleucine and their toxic byproducts accumulate in the blood, plasma, and urine.
An organic acidemia that is characterized by elevated levels of 3-methylglutaconic acid and 3-methylglutaric acid in the urine. (do).
An urea cycle disorder that involves arginase deficiency resulting in elevated levels of plasma arginine. (do).
The finding of blood in feces, usually via laboratory test. (nci).
The noisy expeltion of gas from the mouth. (nci ctcae).
A disorder characterized by a failure of a physiologic function or system (NCI).
A state of profound unconsciousness associated with markedly depressed cerebral activity. Causes include central nervous system damage, intoxication, and metabolic abnormalities.
A mental disorder characterized by personality change, impaired functioning, and loss of touch with reality. (NCI)
its activity declines following weaning. as a result, adult mammals are normally lactose-intolerant and more than 75% of the human adult population suffers from lactase deficiency.

2-ketoglutarate dehydrogenase is an enzyme of the krebs cycle that catalyzes the oxidation of alpha-ketoglutarate to succinyl coa. the deficiency of 2-ketoglutarate dehydrogenase complex results in the disorder of krebs cycle with accumulation of succinyl coa.

a deficiency in this enzyme results in accumulation of 3-hydroxymethylglutaric acid, 3-hydroxyisovaleric acid, 3-methylcrotonylglycine and 3-methylglutaconic acid (cis and trans form), and methylglutaric acid in urine; and ammonia in blood. symptoms include cardiomyopathy, dehydration, hypotonia, lactic acidosis, and pancreatitis.

the excretion of 3-hydroxyisobutyric acid ranged from 170 to 390 mmol/mol of creatinine. the administration of valine increased this to 18,700 mmol/mol of creatinine and reproduced the clinical picture of ketoacidosis.

a deficiency in this enzyme results in accumulation of 3-hydroxyisovaleric acid, 3-methylglutaconic acid, and methylglutaric acid in urine. symptoms include hypoglycemia, low birth weight, coma, seizures, and mental retardation.

The disorder is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous or homozygous mutation in the gene encoding phosphoglycerate dehydrogenase on chromosome 1p12. defects in the gene lead to a decrease of glycine and serine.
patients are relatively asymptomatic but they do exhibit high levels of urinary excretion of 5-oxoproline. patients also exhibit plasma 5-oxoproline levels of about 0.
a defect in this enzyme results in accumulation of 5-aminolevulinic acid or porphobilinogen in both urine and serum. most patients are completely free of symptoms between attacks.

(adenylosuccinase deficiency ; adenylosuccinate monophosphate lyase deficiency) is a rare autosomal recessive disease caused by a mutation in the adsl gene which codes for adenylosuccinate lyase. a deficiency in this enzyme results in accumulation of succinyladenosine in plasma, spinal fluid, and urine.

a defect in liver arginase causes accumulation of ammonia in blood; arginine, creatine, guanidinoacetate, and homoarginine in plasma; urea nitrogen in serum; arginine and homoarginine in spinal fluid; and arginiosuccinate orotic acid, and uracil in urine. symptoms include ataxia, cerebral atrophy, chorea, jaundice, and seizures.
A disorder involving build-up of fatty material and calcium deposition in the arterial wall. It results in partial or complete occlusion of the arterial lumen.

a deficiency in this enzyme results in accumulation of ammonia and ketone bodies in blood; and 2-methyl-3-hydroxybutyric acid, 2-methylacetoacetic acid, 3-hydroxybutyric acid, tiglylglycine, and ketone bodies in urine. symptoms include ketosis, seizures, organic acids in urine, and hyperammonemia.

it is caused by a defect in tryptophan absorption. bacterial degradation of tryptophan in the intestine leads to excessive indole production and thus to indicanuria which, on oxidation to indigo blue, causes a peculiar bluish discoloration of the diaper.

carbamoyl phosphate is derived from catabolism of amino acids into a 1-carbon compound, in which the carbon atom is derived from bicarbonate. the process is exclusively mitochondrial and requires the expenditure of two atp molecules.

signs and symptoms of this disorder usually begin soon after birth and may include breathing problems, seizures, and an irregular heartbeat (arrhythmia). affected individuals typically have low blood sugar (hypoglycemia) and a low level of ketones, which are produced during the breakdown of fats and used for energy.

a deficiency of lysosomal acid lipase causes 2 distinct phenotypes in humans: wolman disease and cholesteryl ester storage disease (cesd). wolman disease is an early-onset fulminant disorder of infancy with massive infiltration of the liver, spleen, and other organs by macrophages filled with cholesteryl esters and triglycerides.

term: Chronic progressive external ophthalmoplegia and kearns-sayre syndrome

definition: two forms of citrullinemia have been described, both having different signs and symptoms, and are caused by mutations in different genes. citrullinemia belongs to a class of genetic diseases called urea cycle disorders.

a deficiency in this enzyme results in accumulation of dihydrothymine, dihydrouracil, thymine, and uracil in urine. symptoms, which present at birth, include metabolic acidosis, difficulty feeding, and seizures.

a defect in dmgdh results in the accumulation of n,n-dimethylglycine and creatinine kinase in serum, and n,n-dimethylglycine in urine. symptoms of this disease include an unusual odor and muscle weakness.

beginning in childhood, this buildup causes signs and symptoms that affect many parts of the body. characteristic features of fabry disease include episodes of pain, particularly in the hands and feet (acroparesthesias); clusters of small, dark red spots on the skin called angiokeratomas; a decreased ability to sweat (hypohidrosis); cloudiness of the front part of the eye (corneal opacity); problems with the gastrointestinal system; ringing in the ears (tinnitus); and hearing loss.
if not appropriately treated, and if fructose is not excluded from the diet, the outcome could be fatal.

(wikipedia) fumarase deficiency is a severe autosomal recessive metabolic disorder characterized by early-onset hypotonia, profound psychomotor retardation, and brain abnormalities, such as agenesis of the corpus callosum, gyral defects, and ventriculomegaly. many patients show neonatal distress, metabolic acidosis, and/or encephalopathy (summary by kerrigan et al.
the active enzyme is a homodimer of 50-kd subunits complexed to pyridoxal-5-phosphate. gabat is present in several tissues in addition to brain and is most active in liver.

a deficiency in this enzyme results in accumulation of l-cysteine, gamma-glutamylcysteine, and glutathione in urine. symptoms, which present at birth, include tall stature, psychosis, and mental retardation.
glutathione synthetase is the second enzyme in the glutathione biosynthesis pathway. it catalyses the condensation of gamma-glutamylcysteine and glycine, to form glutathione.

a deficiency in this enzyme results in accumulation of hawkinsin in urine and plasma; cis-4-hydroxycyclohexylacetic acid, trans-4-hydroxycyclohexylaceid, vanillactic acid, 4-hydroxyphenylpyruvic acid, pyroglutamic acid in urine; and l-tyrosine in plasma. symptoms include ketosis, metabolic acidosis, swimming-pool odor, and mental retardation.

it is an inborn error of metabolism characterized clinically by defective bone mineralization that can be fatal early in infancy.  three more or less distinct types can be identified: (1) type 1 with onset in utero or in early postnatal life, craniostenosis, severe skeletal abnormalities, hypercalcemia, and death in the first year or so of life; (2) type 2 with later, more gradual development of symptoms, moderately severe 'rachitic' skeletal changes and premature loss of teeth; (3) type 3 with no symptoms, the condition being determined on routine studies.

iminoglycinuria is a rare and complex disorder, associated with a number of genetic mutations which cause defects in both renal and intestinal transport systems of glycine and imino acids. symptoms include urolithiasis, excessive imino acids in the urine, and mental retardation.

it is caused by the shortage (deficiency) of an enzyme called galactosylceramidase. this enzyme deficiency impairs the growth and maintenance of myelin, the protective covering around certain nerve cells that ensures the rapid transmission of nerve impulses.

signs and symptoms of vlcad deficiency typically appear during infancy or early childhood and can include low blood sugar (hypoglycemia), lack of energy (lethargy), and muscle weakness. affected individuals are also at risk for serious complications such as liver abnormalities and life-threatening heart problems.

the characteristic phenotype of this condition is quite variable, but may include developmental delay in early childhood, seizures, hypotonia, diarrhea, vomiting, metabolic acidosis, hypoglycemia, ketosis, abnormal urinary compounds, lactic acidemia, and hypertrophic cardiomyopathy.
mat catalyzes the formation of adenosylmethionine from methionine and atp. adenosylmethionine is an important methyl donor in most transmethylation reactions.

a defect in methylmalonate semialdehyde dehydrogenase causes accumulation of 3-aminoisobutyric acid, 3-hydroxyisobutyric acid, 3-hydroxypropionic acid, beta-alanine, lactate, and methylmalonic acid in urine. symptoms inclue failure to thrive, large liver, mental and motor retardation and vomiting.

each episode of fever lasts about 3 to 6 days, and the frequency of the episodes varies among affected individuals. in childhood the fevers seem to be more frequent, occurring as often as 25 times a year, but as the individual gets older the episodes occur less often.

the majority of affected individuals have the multisystem illness with hepatic disease (cholestasis) and neurologic dysfunction evident within weeks of birth. they subsequently manifest severe hypotonia, developmental regression, and typical rotary nystagmus that evolves into opsoclonus.
people with this condition do not make enough of an enzyme called amp deaminase. in most people, amp deaminase deficiency does not cause any symptoms.

serine—pyruvate aminotransferase catalyzes the reaction of serine and pyruvate to produce 3-hydroxypyruvate and l-alanine, as well as the reaction from l-alanine and glyodxylate to pyruvate and glycine. a defect in this results in accumulation of ammonia, glucose and pyruvate in blood; proline, lysine, citrulline, and alanine in plasma; and 2-oxoglutaric acid, fumaric acid, ketone bodies and succinate in urine.
with a single diagnosed patient, rpi deficiency is currently thought to be the rarest disease in the world. (wikipedia) ribose 5-phosphate isomerase deficiency is caused by a mutation in gene rpia.

it can result from an inborn error of sarcosine metabolism, or from severe folate deficiency related to the folate requirement for the conversion of sarcosine to glycine. sarcosine (n-methylglycine) is enzymatically formed from dimethylglycine by dimethylglycine dehydrogenase and converted to glycine by sarcosine dehydrogenase (sardh).

gtp cyclohydrolase i is rate-limiting in the conversion of gtp to tetrahydrobiopterin (bh4), the cofactor for tyrosine hydroxylase, which in turn is the rate-limiting enzyme for dopamine synthesis. patients are characterized by childhood onset dystonia of the legs, progressing to parkinsonism and pseudo-pyramidal deficits, or in adult life with parkinsonism and pseudo-pyramidal signs.

other movement problems can include muscle stiffness (spasticity), tremors, problems with coordination and balance (ataxia), and involuntary jerking movements (chorea). people with sepiapterin reductase deficiency can experience episodes called oculogyric crises.
most patients develop dislocated ocular lenses. later or milder presentations of sod are being reported with increasing frequency.
transaldolase is an enzyme of the reversible part of the pentose phosphate pathway. affected patients have abnormal polyol concentrations in body fluids, mostly in urine.

the th gene provides instructions for making the enzyme tyrosine hydroxylase, which takes part in the pathway that produces a group of chemical messengers called catecholamines, namely dopamine, norepinephrine and epinephrine. dopamine transmits signals to help the brain control physical movement and emotional behavior.

Organic substances added to a pasty mass of inorganic substances that, upon combustion, will leave a porous structure.
Polymeric substances of relatively low molecular weight that can be mixed with additives and hardened by further polymerization during or after a forming or coating process.
Preparations containing substances with antigenic properties administered to activate the immune system, thereby inducing an immune response.

Preparations used to facilitate cutting and other deformation of metal: cutting lubricants, drilling oil and other fluids used for cutting, drilling, grinding, honing, milling, punching, rolling or stamping metal. (might be covered by lubricants and/or heat transferring agents?).
A chemical substance that prevents night blindness or inflammation or dryness of the eyes.
A chemical substance that prevents or relieves scurvy.
A chemical substance that promotes the drainage of vessels.
A chemical substance that quells or blunts the libido.
Substance (e.g, amino acids or minerals) added to animal feed to improve nutrition and health.
Substance (usually organic) which encourages the formation on an even surface upon drying, such as in a polish or coating.
Substance capable of reacting with both the reinforcement and the resin matrix of a composite material.
Substance employed to dissolve and maintain in homogenous solution other ingredients in consumer products, and/or to allow the product to solubilize soils on surfaces and facilitate removal.
Substance introduced between two moving surfaces to reduce the friction between them, improve efficiency, and reduce wear.
Substance or materials used to prevent or slow down spontaneous changes in and ageing of materials: antioxidants, anti-siccatives, heat stabilizers, light stabilizers, scavengers, charge stabilizers.
Substance s applied to textile fibers to prevent their "felting" or forming at mat during processing.

Substance that assists in the formation and the stabilization of emulsions. inclusion of emulsion stabilizers enhances the activity of emulsifiers. emulsion stabilizers prevent or reduce the coalescence of emulsified droplets by modifying the continuous or the disperse phase of the emulsion. .
Substance that burn in a candle to create the flame.
Substance that constitutes a phase in suspension of small globules of two or more liquids that do not mix.
Substance that creates a smooth and shiny surface by mechanical action.
Substance that during reactions with oxidizing agents lose electrons. reducing agents commonly contribute hydrogen to other substances.
Substance that enhances the fluidity of products without significant lowering of the concentration of the active constituents.
Substance that expands and dissolves when wet causing the tablet to break apart and to release the active ingredients.

Substance that has the ability to complex with and inactivate metallic ions. chelation of metal ions helps prevent their adverse effects on the stability or appearance of finished products. chelating agents are also called sequestrants.
Substance that helps keep soils from redepositing onto clothing in the wash water after they have been removed.
Substance that increases the whiteness of a formulation or a substrate.
Substance that is added to a material during processing and may be removed from the finished product, converted into constituents in the finished products, or remains present in the finished product.
Substance that is added to compounded dry powder mixtures of solids and the like to provide adhesive qualities during and after compression to make tablets or cakes.

Substance that is either a non-surface active polymer or a surface-active substance added to a suspension, usually a colloid, to improve the separation of particles and to prevent settling or clumping.
Substance that is involved in a neutralization reaction, a chemical reaction of an acid and a base to form water and a salt.

Substance that is used for expelling products from pressurized containers (aerosol products). the functionality of a propellant depends on its vapor pressure at ambient temperature and its compressibility.
Substance that is used to control insects and mites on plants. horticultural spray oil is usually applied as a dilute spray on plant surfaces.
Substance that is used to cool surfaces.
Substance that is used to decrease or increase the viscosity of finished products.

Substance that is used to enhance the appearance of color of fabric and paper. brightening agents usually absorb light in the ultraviolet and violet region (340-370 nm) of the electromagnetic spectrum, and re-emit light in the blue region (420-470 nm). this causes a "whitening" effect by increasing the overall amount of blue light reflected.
Substance that is used to remove dust and other fine impurities.
Substance that is used to remove soap scum by chemical action. soap scum is a white or gray filmy layer on the surfaces around showers, bathtubs, and sinks.

Substance that is used to retard moisture loss from the product during use. this function is generally performed by hygroscopic materials. the efficacy of humectants depends to a large extent on the ambient relative humidity.
Substance that may be added to other ingredients to make them more hydrophilic or hydrophobic.
Substance that prevent scorch and premature vulcanization of rubber prior to reaching vulcanization temperatures.
Substance that prevents the transfer of dyes from one garment to another in the wash water.
Substance that produces a continuous film on the materialвЂ™s surface upon drying.
Substance that protects surfaces against water absorption and makes water beads.
Substance that provides stain blocking and soil resistance to soft surface cleaners and protectors.

Substance that reduces the tendency of finished products to generate foam on shaking or agitation.
.

Substance that removes colors or whitens, often via oxidation. common chemical bleaches usually include "chlorine bleach", such as sodium hypochlorite, or "oxygen bleach", which contains hydrogen peroxide or a peroxide-releasing compound together with catalysts and activators. many bleaches have strong bactericidal properties, and are also used for sanitizing and disinfecting.
Substance that removes unprotected areas of metal or glass surfaces. etching agents are usually acids or bases.

Substance that thickens the aqueous portions of an aqueous mixture and is commonly employed in thickening various types of emulsions. its action results from its water solubility or hydrophilic nature.

Substance that thickens the lipid portions of a nonaqueous mixture and is commonly employed for thickening or gelling oily materials. its action results from its water insolubility and compatibility with various lipids.
Substance used in fragrance mixtures to carry fragrance components. fragrance carriers are usually odorless compounds.

Substance used to form thin films on hard surfaces in order to add specific surface properties, such as corrosion, oxidation, electrical, or wear resistance, appearance, optical properties, or thermal protection.
Substance used to inactivate or remove active chlorine.
Substance used to modify the textile or fiber surface so as to render it more hydrophilic and consequently resistant to soiling with oil, grease or fatty type agents.
Substance which helps to break down lipids, proteins, and polysaccharides usually by enzymatic or other action.

Substance, which according to the international fragrance association, is "any basic substance used in the manufacture of fragrance materials for its odorous, odor-enhancing or blending properties. fragrance ingredients may be obtained by chemical synthesis from synthetic, fossil, or natural raw materials, or by physical operations from natural sources. 
the function comprises aroma chemicals, essential oils, natural extracts, distillates and isolates, oleoresins, etc." additionally, for purposes of labeling under "fragrance" or "parfum", the term fragrance ingredient signifies "any natural or synthetic substance or substances used solely to impart an odor to a cosmetic product.

Substances (usually inert, fibrous materials) used to improve physical properties, such as tensile strength, hardness, abrasion resistance, and tear resistance of materials such as rubber and plastics.
Substances addd to latex formulation used for dipping operations that prevent the formation of thin free-standing sheets when the form is removed from the latex.
Substances added to  rubber to prevent  cracking  (e.g., sun checking) of the finished product.
Substances added to a dye bath to ensure that the dye is retained on the fabric.
Substances added to a dye bath to slow the rate of dyeing and to prevent rapid exhaustion of  the dye.

Substances added to a liquid to  prevent  or  retard oxidation or polymerization that re'sults in the formation of a "skin" on the liquid's surface,  either during storage in a container or on exposure  to air.
Substances added to a liquid to reduce evaporation at the liquid surface.
Substances added to a material that cause it to increase in volume and become softer (e.g.,  a low molecular weight liquid absorbed by rubber).
Substances added to a process or product to consume, neutralize, or inactivate small amounts or by-products, degradation products, impurities, ect..
Substances added to a suspending medium to promote and stabilize the uniform dispersion of extremely fine solid particles, often of colloidal size.
Substances added to a wash bath to remove traces of materials suc as soap, contaminants, and residues (e.g., as used in automatic dishwashers.).
Substances added to fuels to prevent premature ignition in internal combustion engines.
Substances added to liquids to lower the freezing point which prevents and remove ice formation.
Substances added to lubricants to inhibit seizing of a metal part as it moves against a metal surface.
Substances added to materials (e.g., pretoleum products, varnish, and rosin oil) to enhance fluorescence.
Substances added to materials (suc as plastics and paints) to protect against the degradative effects of ultraviolet radiation.
Substances added to materials used as acid  pickling agents to retard or prevent the chemical action of the acid on the base metal.
Substances added to paints and coatings to prevent the downward movement of a paint film between application and setting.
Substances added to paints, varnishes, or other coatings to disperse incident light rays, thus reducing the gloss of the dried film and producing a matte finish.
Substances added to paper pulp stock to promote the uniform formation of paper on the fourdrinier machine.
Substances added to plastic formulations to prevent softening or an  increase in flexibility of  the plastic.
Substances added to plastics that exude to the surface and act as lubricants, thus improving slip characteristics.
Substances added to polymeric material ( e.g., rubber, polyurethane, fibers) to prevent breakdown of the polymeric chain by hydrolysis.
Substances added to polymeric materials to increase their resistance to impact.
Substances added to polymers prior to processing to reduce friction, improve flow characteristics, or improve wetting properties.
Substances added to soil to supply chemical elements needed for plant nutrition.
Substances added to textiles during processing or finishing that reduce the tendency of the fibers to "ball up" (pill).
Substances added to textiles to improve their resistance to abrasion.
Substances added to yarn or fabric to increase their weight or to act as filling agent.
Substances appled to aubstrates such as textiles to prevent oil wetting.
Substances applied as a protective layer to selected areas of a surface to retard or prevent printing .
Substances applied to a surface or added to a compound to increase the  tack of a deposited adhesive film.
Substances applied to solids (e.g., electrodes) to promote the emisison of electrons.
Substances applied to substrates such a fabrics, yarn, paper products, or plaster to increase abrasive resistance, stiffness, strength, smoothness, or reduce absorption.
Substances applied to textile fibers or yarns to prevent slippage during weaving.
Substances capable of destroying a dye or mordant in a fabric to produce a colorless image upon a colored background.
Substances entrained in a high velocity stream used to clean, cut, or finish surfaces.
Substances incorporated into or applied  to the surface of a substrate to prevent slippage  (e.g., by increasing surface roughage).
Substances incorporated into or applied to the surface of materials to slow down or to prevent combustion.
Substances or materials added to product that are used to prevent the corrosion of mettalic materials.

Substances or materials used to modify the flow characteristics of other substances, or mixtures, to which they are added: pour point depressants, thickeners, thixotropic agents, turbulence suppressor, viscosity index improvers.

Substances or materials used to reproduce a permanent image: toners and developers for photocopying, toner additives, printing ink, and developers for printing forms. not: photo chemicals, fixing agents.

Substances or mixtures that are characterized by chemical stability but that may be made undergo rapid chemical change without an outside sources of oxygen, rapidly producing a large quantity of energy accompanied by bursting or expansion.
Substances ormaterials used to avoid condensation on surfaces and in the atmosphere.
Substances that  induce the union of small droplets of a liquid to form larger unit liquid volumes.
Substances that  prevent or retard the discoloration of a metal surface  due to the formation of  a thin  film of oxide, sulfide,  etc.
Substances that  retard the gumming  of vegetable oils while promoting  lubrication.
Substances that accelerate or control the drying  or hardening of formulations such as paints, varnishes, lacquers, inks, or sealants.
Substances that adsorb on the surface of mineral particles to provide a water repellent film that improves adherence of the mineral to air bubbles.
Substances that aid in the detection or determination of condition or composition of other substances, usually by visual means.

Substances that are used in conductive circuits as components (e.g., terminals or plates of batteries, electrolytic cells, or arc welding equipment) that establish contact with a nonmetallic part of the circuit.
Substances that are used to emit light at high temperatures; e.g., light bulb filaments.
Substances that can provide ionic conductivity when fused or in solution.
Substances that cause chemical reactions to start and are themselves chemically change (e.g., organic peroxides used in polymerization reactions).
Substances that cause liquids to setup into jelly-like semisolids.
Substances that cause solids to settle from solution or suspension, usually by chemical action.
Substances that conduct electrical energy poorly, thus acting as a barrier to electrical conduction.
Substances that depress the temperature at which solids begin to separate from a liquid, such as paraffin wax separating from a solution of petroleum oil.
Substances that dissolves and separate a solid from a mixture with an insoluble solid.
Substances that drive away insects from the point of application.
Substances that emit visible or invisible radiation upon absorption of energy in the form of photons, charged particles, or chemical change.
Substances that facilitate the solution of partially soluble solutes in solvents.
Substances that form a colloidal system that exhibits a reversible reduction in viscosity upon mechanical working and that may be used, for example, to prevent running of paints.
Substances that form a solid or semi-solid dispersion of a fluid lubricant or increase the viscosity of paints, coatings, etc.
Substances that ignite spontaneously upon impact, bursting, or contact.
Substances that impart flexibility or workability to a polymer.
Substances that impart wrinkle resistance to a fabric.
Substances that increase dye penetrations into textile products during processing.
Substances that induce mixtures such as liquids, supersaturated solutions, saturated vapors, and polymers to form crystals or droplets, or that modify crystal grain structure, as in metals.
Substances that induce the aggregation of semisolid particles into coherent clots, curds, or masses.
Substances that induce the aggregation of suspended solid particles into small clumps or tufts (e.g., aggregation of ore particles during flotation process).
Substances that inhibit the degradation by light of materials such as dyes and polymers.
Substances that inhibit the solidification of paints, lacquers, and varnishes during aging.
Substances that initiate explosives and are activated by such means as flame, spark, or friction (e.g., explosives in blasting caps).
Substances that irritate the eyes, causing tearing.
Substances that make a product more elastic (e.g.. an additive that contribute elasticity to a resin.
Substances that poorly conduct various forms of energy (e.g., heat, electricity), thereby acting as a barrier to its transmission.
Substances that prevent deterioration of textiles by atmospheric fumes, particularly those caused by combustion or those with and acid character.
Substances that prevent or  inhibit  the  loss  of ductility of a metal.
Substances that prevent scale, a thin layer of metal oxides, from forming on metal surfaces.
Substances that prevent the agglomeration of resin particles in wood pulping operations.
Substances that prevent the color from rubbing off textiles.
Substances that prevent the concentration of pigments at the surface of a paint film.
Substances that prevent the migration of an ingredient of a mixture to the surface.
Substances that promote full development or maturation of fruits and vegetables.
Substances that promote the destruction of cellulosic materials during the processing of wool.
Substances that promote the formation and stability of a suspension of fine particles of a liquid in another liquid.
Substances that provide food or energy for  the cultured growth of microorganisms.
Substances that react with a dye on a fiber to improve fastness (e.g., diazonium compounds used for after treatment of direct dyeings).
Substances that react with the end of a growing polymer chain, stopping growth.
Substances that reduce friction head losses (i.e., drag) in fluids in motion and between a fluid and a conduit surface.
Substances that remove or inactives water hardness minerals, principally calcium and magnesium.
Substances that remove or reduce the adhesive properties of materials.
Substances that remove the discoloration of a metal surface due to the formation of a thin film of oxide, sulfide, etc..
Substances that remove unexposed radiation-sensitive salts from developed photographic film and paper.
Substances that removes scale (e.g., coatings or crusts of oxides) from the surface of metals in reducing, oxidizing, or electrolytic processes.
Substances that solubilize lignin in wood and facilitate the separation of cellulosic materials.
Substances that terminate the growth of a molecular chain and form a new radical that can act as the initiator for a new chain.
Substances that undergo changes in observable properties to indicate changes in water vapor pressure (humidity).
Substances that whiten substrates by masking the yellow cast.
Substances that will conduct electricity.
Substances that, in effect, increase the length of a molecular chain by suppressing chain terminating reaction.
Substances that, when added to an agitated or aerated liquid, will promote the formation and stability of a foam or froth.
Substances that, when added to coatings compositions, increase the ability of the coating to resist mechanical damage.
Substances that, when applied to a permeable surface, prevent the migration of materials.
Substances used  to desorb material  from  an  adsorbent (e.g., removal of minerals  from  ion exchange  agents).
Substances used  to prevent the formation of iron oxides on ferrous metals and alloys.
Substances used  to reduce or eliminate frothing or foaming in a treatment or process.
Substances used (e.g., in mining) that reduce the moisture content of filter cake.
Substances used as coating or void(e.g., leakage).
Substances used as the source for a layer of metal deposited on another surface, or that aid in such deposition.
Substances used during petroleum refining precesses to remove petroleum wax from refinery streams, especially to separate waxes from oils.
Substances used for softening materials (e.g., textiles, paper, gum) to improve feel , to facilitate finishing processes, or to impart flexibility or workability.
Substances used for synthesis of other chemicals: monomers, prepolymers.
Substances used for the preservation of dead bodies, usually human.
Substances used for the reversible interchange of ions (or sometimes inorganic complexex) with an aqueous phase ( e.g., zeolites, ion exchange resins or liquid ion exchanger).
Substances used for their magnetic or magnetizable properties, e.g., in transformer cores or on magnetic tape.
Substances used for visual detection of acidity or basicity of solutions.
Substances used in a bleach bath to promote penetration by the bleach and improve  bleaching action.
Substances used in lubricating and automotive oils to reduce the effect of temperature on their viscosity.
Substances used in ore flotation to prevent small particles of the desired mineral ("fine") from adhering to the bulk gangue (or waste) material.
Substances used in photography to increase the density of an image in a film plate or paper.
Substances used in printing to increase the density of the tone, color, or image.
Substances used in products to make them nontransparent; they may also enhance luster, control texture, stabilize color, or promote craze resistance.
Substances used in the irreversible joining of metals by a nonferrous alloy at high temperature.
Substances used in the leather industry to remove dehairing chemicals from skins and to make them flaccid prior to tanning.
Substances used in the manufacture of a photographic emulsion that reduce its sensitivity to light or other radiation.

Substances used in the manufacture of steel to produce a case-hardened surface by absorbing  carbon or nitrogen into the alloy (e.g. , from a molten  bath (cyaniding) or in contact with ammonia (gas nitriding)).
Substances used prior to drycleaning or laundering of textile to loosen or dissolve soil.
Substances used to alter or stabilize the hydrogen ion concentration (ph): acids, alkalis, buffers.
Substances used to assist in reducing materials to fine particulate matter during grinding.
Substances used to assist in removal of sizes (e.g., removal of starch from textiles).
Substances used to block or attenuate x-rays, e.g., for shielding or medical diagnosis.
Substances used to change the properties of polymers, especially thermosetting plastics or elastomers, usually by increasing the molecular weight (e.g., by crosslinking, condensation,  or addition).
Substances used to combine with other substances (mainly metal ions) to form complexes or precipitates or induce coagulation.
Substances used to control finely divided solid particles of powdered or ground materials to reduce their discharges into the air.
Substances used to control microorganisms occuring in pulpwood.
Substances used to control the rate of cure of mortar or concrete.
Substances used to create a permanent photographic image.
Substances used to destroy (break) an emulsion or to prevent its formation.
Substances used to dissolve and facilitate the separation of, usually from mixtures, desired components or unwanted impurities.
Substances used to dissolve and remove gum-like substances from natural fibers, (e.g., sericin, a glue-like substance, from silk).
Substances used to make materials impervious to penetration by water.
Substances used to make visible an exposed, latent photographic image.
Substances used to neutralize the effect of optical brighteners.
Substances used to prepare metal surfaces for coating, electroplating, or passivating a chemically active metal surface.
Substances used to prevent  clogging of filters by removing particles that would otherwise not pass through the filter.
Substances used to prevent precipitation of inorganic ions or compounds by inhibiting crystal formation, dispersing finely divided particulate matter, or combining with them by forming complexes.
Substances used to promote the even dyeing of textiles or paper.
Substances used to promote the uniform coating and adhesion of agricultural chemicalasa (except fertilizers) onto plant surfaces.
Substances used to protect wool and silk during wet processing.
Substances used to purify water by removal of both anions and cations.
Substances used to reduce a polymer's degree of polymerization.
Substances used to reduce or eliminate the gloss or sheen on textiles fibers, yarn, and fabrics.
Substances used to reduce the explosion potential of flammable materials.
Substances used to regulate the speed of a (chemical) process: accelerators, activators, catalysts, hardeners, inhibitors, siccatives, cross linking agents etc. not: stabilizers.
Substances used to remove chemically bound or otherwise associated water from a substance by chemical, catalytic, or other means.
Substances used to remove dissolves or entrained gases, (e.g., the use of nitrogen to purge oxygen from solutions).
Substances used to remove dyes from fabrics so that they can be redyed.
Substances used to remove grease, usually by solvent action or emulsification.
Substances used to remove ice from, or prevent its accumulation on, a surface or in a liquid (e.g., preventing ice formation in fuel lines or carburetors).
Substances used to remove impurities during purification processes.
Substances used to remove inks, coloring materials, and fillers from paper.
Substances used to remove or destroy hazardous materials or germs.
Substances used to remove oxides from and to clean the surfaces of metals, or to promote the fusion of metals or minerals.
Substances used to remove plated metals from a base metal (e.g., gold plating from copper).
Substances used to remove radioactive substances from surfaces, liquids, gases, or the environment.
Substances used to remove residual or free chlorine or hypochlorite from materials (i.e from textiles, wood, pulp, water supplies, stacks gases).
Substances used to remove tar from a material.
Substances used to remove traces of asphalt from petroleum streams during  petroleum processing.
Substances used to remove water vapor from  gases such as air, (e.g., by absorption or hydrate formation).
Substances used to remove wax from surfaces (e.g., floor polish or wax from linoleum).
Substances used to removed polymeric coating materials from surfaces ( e.g., photoresist from printed circuit boards.).
Substances used to reomove oxidized iron (rust) from the surface of metals.
Substances used to retard or prevent deterioration cause by ozone.
Substances used to soften rubber during a  reclaiming process by reducing the degree of crosslinking.
Substances used to surround or encase solid or liquid matter to isolate it.
Substances used to treat various substrates (e.g., textiles, leather or paper) to make them resistant to wetting by water.

Substances used with textiles, plastics, elastomers or other materials to reduce the tendency to accumulate electrostatic charges either by being inherently conductive or by absorbing moisture from air.
Substances with surface active properties that wet floating or suspended particles, allowing them to disperse or precipitate.
Substances, not indigenous to plants, that control the rate of growth or maturation of plants, especially fruits and vegetables.
Substances, often a component of drillings muds or fluids, that prevent loss of fluid into the rock formation during petroleum drilling.

Substances, such as optical brighteners, that emit visible light as a direct consequence of the absorption of shorter wave length radiation such as ultraviolet light. the emission of radiation ceases when the stimulating radiation is discontinued.
Substances, used in metals treating, that react with a substrate metal to form a protective insoluble coat of metal phosphate (e.g., to protect a metal surface before applying paint.).
Substances, usually a metallic salt or an acid, that fix a dye in or on a substance (e.g., a textile fiber) by combining with the dye to form an insoluble component.
Substances, usually acids, used to remove oxides from metal surfaces by an immersion process.
Substances, when added to paint or coating formulations, prevent of small bow-shaped depression (" fish eyes" or "alligatoring") in the dried film.
Substances/materials added to rubber to aid and hasten vulcanization: vulcanizing accelerators and vulcanization assistants.
Substances/materials used as a source for a layer of metal deposited on another surface, or that aid in such a deposition.
Substances/materials used for treating hides and skins.

Substances/materials used to admix with solid materials, which retain their original form: impregnating agents for leather, paper, textile and wood. not: flame retardants, conserving agents, pesticides.
Substances/materials used to concentrate and obtain minerals from ores: flotation oil, flotation depressants.
Substances/materials used to control finely divided solid particles of powdered or ground materials to reduce their discharge into the air.

Substances/materials used to form physically, by expansion of compressed gases or vaporization of liquid, or chemically by decomposition evolving a gas, a foam or cellular structure in a plastic or rubber material: chemical or physical blowing agents, expanding agents, frothers.
Substances/materials used to lower the surface and/or interfacial tension of liquids and promote cleaning, wetting, dispersion etc.
Substances/materials used to produce, enhance, or mask odour. not: food additives, cosmetics.
Suppresses abnormal rhythms of the heart, and therefore counters the symtoms of cardiac arrythmia.

Surfactant that aids in the dissolution of an ingredient (solute) in a medium in which it is not otherwise soluble. the process of solubilization generally requires that the solute becomes part of the micelle formed by the surfactant.
Surfactant that does not have positive or negative charges anywhere in the molecule.
Surfactant that has a negative charge in the molecule, and may be in the acid or salt form.
Surfactant that has a positive charge in the molecule, and is associated with a negative anion.
Surfactant that has both positive and negative charges in the molecule.
Surfactant that has the ability to enhance the water solubility of another surfactant.

Surfactant that increases the foaming capacity of surfactants - cleansing agents, or to stabilize foams in general. its action results from increasing the surface viscosity of the liquid which surrounds the individual bubbles in a foam.
Surfactant that is employed to prepare emulsions (i.e., an oil-miscible liquid suspended in a water-miscible liquid, or visa versa).
Surfactant used for cleaning purposes and as emulsifiers. in this function, surfactants reduce the surface tension of water, wet body surfaces, emulsify or solubilize oils, and suspend soil.
Surfactant used for fabric softening and often to reduce static cling.
Surfactant used for hair softening in personal care products.
Surfactants other than soap used as cleaning agents or as components of formulated cleaning products.

Surfactants that, when added to water, cause it to penetrate more easily into, or to spread over the surface of, another material by reducing the surface tension of water.
.
Susbstances used to transmit heat to or remove heat from another material.
Susbtances that aid in removing soil, which results from processing, from textile products during scouring or boiling.
Susbtances that change the amount or character of deposits in combustion chambers.
Susbtances that reduce the sensitivity of an explosive to heat or impact.
A chemical substance that tends to cause spasms.
A chemical substance that treats or counters the symptoms of akathisia.
A chemical substance that treats or counters the symptoms of amnesia.
A chemical substance that treats or counters the symptoms of anorexia.
A chemical substance that treats or counters the symptoms of asthma.
A chemical substance that treats or counters the symptoms of autism.
A chemical substance that treats or counters the symptoms of azotemia.
A chemical substance that treats or counters the symptoms of beriberi.
A chemical substance that treats or counters the symptoms of oesteoarthritis.
A chemical substance that treats or counters the symptoms of parkinson's disease.
A chemical substance that treats or counters the symptoms of pollagra, a deficiency disease caused by a lack of nicotinic acid or its precursor tryptophan in the diet.
A chemical substance that treats or suppresses the inflammation of the mucosa of the mouth.
В A chemical substance that inhibits the maturation, growth or spread of tumor cells. (NCI)

A chemical substance used in the treatment of acute or chronic hypertension regardless of pharmacological mechanism. Antihypertensive agents include diuretics, alpha-adrenergic and beta-adrenergic antagonists, angiotensin-converting enzyme inhibitors, calcium channel blockers, ganglionic blockers, and vasodilator agents. (NCI)

A small molecule which increases (activator) or decreases (inhibitor) the activity of an (allosteric) enzyme by binding to the enzyme at the regulatory site (which is different from the substrate-binding catalytic site).
A chemical substance which can be utilized for production of energy in the organism.
A fatty acid which is required for basic funtions in the human body, and needs to be obtained from food due to insufficient production in the body.
A chemical substance that is produced by all organisms.
Substances produces in animals or plant that regulate the activity of certain organs or control processes in other parts of the plant.
A chemical substance that is produced by humans and is essential for immediate survival.
A chemical substance that modifies the immune response or the functioning of the immune system (as by the stimulation of antibody formation or the inhibition of white blood cell activity).
a chemical substance or preparation that interrupts or deminishes insulin signaling, and promotes the opposite biochemical action.

A chemical substance that supports the formation and maintenance of a structurally-sound and functioning cell or organelle membrane. Phospholipids form a bilayer and maintain the stability of the membrane structure together with proteins, and other lipids (i.e. cholesterol) which further strengthen it and decrease its permeability.
A chemical substance produced during metabolism process, as an intermediate or end-product.
A chamical substance, other than a neurotransmitter, released by a neuron and transmitting information to other neurons, altering their activities.
A chemicalВ substance that affects transport of neurotransmitters across a cell membrane.
A chamical substance in food, further ingested and utilized by an organism for its well-being, growth and reproduction.
A chemical substance that binds to or interferes with binding to any of the opioid receptor subtypes, thereby blocking the actions of opioid agonists. (nci).
A chemical substance that affects osmosis. osmolytes are soluble in the cell or in the fluid between cells, and are utilized by cells during water stress to maintain the cell volume.

Substance that gains electrons during their reaction with a reducing agent. oxidizing agents commonly contribute oxygen to other substances. in consumer products, most oxidizing agents are bleaching agents.
comment: from EPA list of function for chemicals

definition: A chemical substance that inhibits the actions of the parasympathetic nervous system.
A chemical substance that binds toВ phosphateВ and forms an insoluble compound. includes simple cations as well as salts.
A chemical substance that inhibits the transport of sodium ions via sodium channels in the cell membrane.
A chemical substance that induces oxidative stress, either by generating reactive oxygen species or by inhibiting antioxidant systems. (wikipedia).
A chemical substance or preparation that causes the breakdown of proteins into smaller peptides.
A chemical substance that can be converted into a vitamin in animal tissues.
A chemical substance that transmit signals from a receptor to a target within a living cell.
A chemical substance that is naturally produced by some organisms and not essential to their short-term survival.
A chemical substance which is of low molecular weight, and is a very strong iron-chelator, secreted by microorganisms such as bacteria and fungi.
A chemical substance that particpiates in signal transduction processes in a living cell.
A chemical substance that inhibits the transport of potassium ions via channels in the cell membrane.
A chemical substance utilized during the process of steroid production.
A chemical element that occurs in very small amounts in organisms and is essential for many physiological and biochemical processes.В .
A protein that increasesВ gene transcriptionВ of a gene or set of genes. most activators areВ dna-binding proteinsВ that bind toВ enhancersВ orВ promoter-proximal elements.
Any substance that interacts with tubulin to inhibit or promote polymerisation of microtubules.
A chemicalВ substanceВ thatВ uncoupleВ oxidation from phosphorylation in the metabolic cycle so that atp synthesis does not occur.

A chemical that is generated in a metabolic process and is destined to be excreted from the body. It commonly consists of water, nitrogenous compounds or carbon dioxide and can be a metabolic byproduct or a degradation product (such as urobilin metabolised from bilirubin which is a degradation product of hemoglobin).
a chemical substance or preparation that triggers an immune response expressed as inflammation in the body of animals and humans.
A chemical substance that causes a decrease in total blood lipids.
A chemical substance that causes an increase in total blood lipids.
Sudden spurts of algal growth, which can affect water quality adversely and indicate potentially hazardous changes in local water chemistry. (source: us epa).
A process in which a lipid molecules is translocated between cellular sites or compartments.
A process in which charged molecules and solutes are passed into or out of a cell.
A process that involves interference with, or restraint of, the activities of cell membrane glycoproteins selectively permeable to calcium ions. (NCI).

A process that is enzymatically-catalized, in which complex molecules are degraded to simpler molecules and energy is released. This can be facilitated by biologic molecules, biologic complexes, or subcellular components.

A process of movement of chemical species under the influence of a concentration difference and as a result of random thermal agitation. The species will move from the high concentration area to the low concentration area till the concentration is uniform in the whole phase. (NCI)
A process that consists of activities of biologic molecules, complexes, or subcellular components that preserve DNA integrity through faithful DNA replication, DNA repair, or recombination. (NCI).
A process that involves adding/removing chemical moieties to/from DNA, including methylation, phosphorylation, dephosphorylation, etc. (NCI).
A process that involves enzymatic restoration of DNA structure after chemical, radiation, or spontaneous damage. (NCI).

A process that involves series of chemical modifications of a drug compound by enzymatic activity that make the substrate (drug) more water soluble to allow its clearance from the body. Drug metabolism occurs in two phases: Phase I (biotransformation) involves oxidation, hydroxylation reduction, and hydrolysis. Phase II (conjugation) involves synthesis and conjugation. (NCI).
A process by which mechanisms, functions, or activities exhibited by tumors or pathogens to withstand previously toxic drugs. (NCI).
A process that is involved in translocation of a drug from one site or compartment to another. (NCI).
A process that involves cellular uptake of extracellular materials within membrane-limited vacuoles or microvesicles. Endosomes play a central role in endocytosis. (NCI).
A process, either subcellular or molecular, that is involved in storing and generating metabolic energy.
A process that involves a change in the quality of the existing state of function of a biological molecule (usually protein, RNA, or DNA) that possesses catalytic activity. (NCI).
A process that involves initiation of function of a biological molecule that possesses catalytic activity. (NCI)
A process that involves interference with, or restraint of, the function of a biological molecule that possesses catalytic activity. (NCI).
A process that involves initiation of function, following prior inhibition, of a biological molecule that possesses catalytic activity. (NCI).
A process that involves alteration (typically disruption) of activity of a physically or functionally coordinated biological complex that possesses catalytic activity. (NCI).
A process that cellular release of secretory products from within membrane-limited vesicles or granules. (NCI).
A process that involves catabolism or anabolism of fatty acids in an organism.

A process by which at least one of the participants has one or more electrons that singly occupy an electron orbital. Free radical processes may promote or prevent damage to tissues in which they arise. (NCI).
A process that involves transcription of genetically encoded information into an intermediary message (messenger RNA) and subsequent translation into a functional protein. (NCI).
The process that involves physical translocation of glucose from one site or compartment to another, typically to provide energy source to cells.

A process that consists of the initiation of subcellular or molecular processes directly involved in the physical translocation from one site or compartment to another (typically, extracellular to intracellular) of the simple C6H12O6 monosaccharide, glucose, that acts as an energy source for cells. (NCI).

A process that involves interference with, or restraint of, subcellular or molecular processes directly involved in the physical translocation from one site or compartment to another (typically, extracellular to intracellular) of the simple C6H12O6 monosaccharide, glucose, that acts as an energy source for cells. (NCI).
A process by which the body maintains a consistent internal environment within a narrow range of variation. It is important to the continuation of life. (NCI).
A process that is initated by a chemical or mechanical stimulus and results in a specific cellular response. (NCI).
A process that involves catabolism or anabolism of lipids in an organism.

A process that involves cellular and biochemical mechanisms that localize and control oxidation/reduction reactions, or that constrain their byproducts, in order to maintain cellular health and homeostasis. (NCI).
A process that involves mechanisms that promote the translocation of a peptide from one location to another. (NCI).
The process by which phagocytes engulf and digest microorganisms and cellular debris; an important defense against infection. (NCI).
A process that involves catabolism or anabolism of phospholipids in an organism.

The process through which light energy, water, and carbon dioxide are converted to carbohydrate and oxygen in the presence of chlorophyll. Occurs in plants, algae, cyanobacteria and lichens. (BioTech Life Science Dictionary) (NCI).

A process that involves the biosynthesis of new (often sets of distinct, functionally related) protein products, usually involving new mRNA transcripts, typically in response to an activating stimulus. (NCI).
A process that involves active cellular mechanisms that directly promote the transport of a protein across the plasma membrane into a cell. (NCI).

A process that is used to denote the transcription of DNA into RNA.  The biochemical machinery includes sequence-specific DNA binding proteins that directly act in the regulation of the transcription process, other protein factors that participate in the assembly of the transcription complex, and RNA polymerase. (NCI).
The process of the translocation of RNA molecules from one cellular location to another, such as transport from the nucleus to the cytoplasm. (NCI).

The process of the intercellular or intracellular transfer of information (biological activation/inhibition) through a signal pathway. In each signal transduction system, an activation/inhibition signal from a biologically active molecule (e.g., hormone, neurotransmitter, etc.) is transferred to a receptor molecule through a physical binding interaction that alters the conformational and functional state of the receptor molecule and promotes an alteration in cell function. (NCI).
The process of repression of any of several ways in which living cells of an organism communicate with one another, whether by direct contact between cells or by means of chemical signals. (NCI).
A process that involves the synthesis a nascent RNA transcript. (NCI).
A process, wither subcellular or molecular, that is involved in translocation of a biological molecule across a cell membrane from one site or compartment to another. (NCI)
A process that involves the catabolism of phospholipids in an organism.
A cellular process involving physiological response to external stressors, aiming to restort cell homeostasis and protect the cell from unsuitable environmental conditions.
A cellular process that involved the passing of a molecular signal in more than one pathway.
A process that prevents inappropriate or premature programmed cell death. includes a variety of coordinated and systematic changes, both physiological and genetic.
A process that support the viability of cells.
The cellular process involving physiological response to stimuli.
The process by which a cell responds to substances in its environment.
The process of cell attachment to another cell or to a cell compartment, mediated by specific molecules on the cell surface.
The process of cell death caused by damage to cell membranes.
The process of cell development in size as part of the cell life cycle.
The process of cell growth and division as part of the cell life cycle.
The process of cell movement to specific location, induced by response to signals.
The process of formation of multiple cells from one parent cell, as part of the cell life cycle.
The process of natural degradation of cell components and their recycling within the cell.
The process of naturally-occurring and programmed cell death.
The process of platelet association, assisted by adhesion molecules.
The process of premature cell death due to injury.
The process of programmed death of immune cells, as a result of cytokine-mediated response to microbial infection .
The process of suppressing the growth and multiplication of cells.
The process resulting in termination of all vital functions of a cell.
The process that leads to a formation of specialized cells as part of an embryo development.
A chemical reaction comprising of adding oxygen atom to a compound, accompanied by a loss of electrons and formation of free radicals.

A chemical reaction in which a water molecule is added to a compound, often involving splitting or cleavage of the molecule. the hydroxyl group is incorporated into one fragment of the compound and the hydrogen atom in the other.
A chemical reaction in which nitric oxide covalently attaches to a sulfur atom in an organic thiol.
A chemical reaction involving a covalent chemical or biochemical addition of carbohydrate or glycosyl groups to other chemicals, by glycosyl transferases.
A chemical reaction involving electron-transfer from a reducing agent (reductant) to an oxidizing agent (oxidant), which is being reduced.
A chemical reaction involving oxidative attack from free radicals on a lipid molecule, resulting in its degradation. .
A chemical reaction involving the catalyzed removal of phosphate groups from biological molecules, by phosphatases.
A chemical reaction involving the creation of a phosphate derivative of an organic molecule. this is usually achieved by transferring a phosphate group from atp via the action of a kinase.
A chemical reaction of polymer formation from repetitive bonding of smaller molecules (monomers).
A chemical reaction that involves removal of an acetyl group from an organic compound (as covalent chemical reaction or post-translational biochemical reaction).
A chemical reaction that involves the covalent linkage of an acetyl group into an organic molecule (nci with adaptation).
A chemical reaction that involves the in which the hydrogen ion concentration of a solution is decreased, resulting in an increase in alkalinity. .
A chemical reaction which involves adding a methyl group to another molecule, resulting in alteration of to their activity (such as methylation of proteins or nucleic acids in the body).
The process of narrowing of the blood vessels.
The process of widening of the blood vessels.
A process that involves the induction of humoral or cell-mediated reaction of the immune system to a bacterial antigen or infection. (NCI).
A process that involves the induction of humoral or cell-mediated reaction of the immune system to a viral antigen or infection. (NCI).
A process involving a cascade of events by which coagulation factors interact to form a fibrin clot.
A process involving any action of the immune system that is triggered by internal or external stimuli.

A process that is part of innate immunity. It occurs when injured tissues induce release of vasodilatory, opsonizing, and chemotactic mediators that attract macrophages and leukocytes to phagocytize and destroy foreign substances; dilate local blood vessels increasing local blood flow; increase capillary permeability; produce edematous swelling; and induce pain. Plasma- and cell-derived inflammatory mediators include Prostaglandins, Leukotrines, Cytokines, Lymphokines, Monokines, PAF, Histamine, Bradykinin, Complement, and Interferons. (NCI Thesaurus).
A process that involves the formation of organs during development. (NCI).
A process that involves initiation of a set of stimulated platelet activities involved in aggregation of platelets and fibrin during blood coagulation. (NCI).
A process that involves the reproduction or reconstitution of a lost or injured part. (NCI).

as the krebs cycle is an aerobic process, in normal cells lactate production is reserved for anaerobic conditions. however, cancer cells preferentially utilize glucose for lactate production via this “aerobic glycolysis”, even when oxygen is plentiful.
A process of an underdevelopment or incomplete development of a tissue or organ.
A process resulting in an alteration in the natural structure of dna.
A process that results in a development of an ulcer.
The alteration of the genetic material of an organism, resulting in gene mutation.
The process of formation of local necrotis tissue resulting from restricted blood suply to the tissue.
The process of physiological degeneration.
The process of swelling of a cell, usually as part of necrotic cell death.
The proess leading to development of a disease or to death.
The transformation of normal cells to neoplastic cells.

A process that involves a specific humoral or cell-mediated immune response against autologous (self) antigens. An autoimmune process may produce or be caused by autoimmune disease and may be developmentally complex, not necessarily pathological, and possibly pervasive. (NCI).
A process that involves the unregulated growth of cancer cells insofar as growth control and contact inhibition. (NCI).

A process that involves the exposure to DNA-damaging agents and subsequent energy expenditures by a cell to repair DNA damage. Genotoxic stress elicits biochemical responses that either enhance cell survival or lead to cell death. These biochemical responses include DNA-damage-inducible repair and increasing expression of a variety of proteins by both transcriptional and post-transcriptional mechanisms.  Genotoxic stresses frequently activate signal transduction pathways that originate in the cell membrane or cytoplasm, triggering similar phosphorylation cascades to those induced by the activation of cell-surface receptors. (NCI).

A constellation of responses that occur when an organism is exposed to excessive heat and other environmental stresses. Responses include synthesis of some proteins, repression of other proteins, and expression of new proteins. (From Segen, Dictionary of Modern Medicine, 1992) (NCI).

The spread or migration of cancer cells from one part of the body (the organ in which it first appeared) to another. The secondary tumor contains cells that are like those in the original (primary) tumor. (NCI).
Mitochondrial Damage involves any process that leads to dysfunction of mitochondria, whether by oxidative damage, mutation of mitochondrial DNA or other by means. (NCI).

The formation of new or recent blood vessels. The vasculature network is critical to the development of neoplasms. As the tumor burden grows, vascular endothelial cells are recruited to form new blood vessels as an increased demand for blood and nourishment is required. (NCI).

A process involving disturbance in the prooxidant-antioxidant balance in favor of the former, leading to potential damage. Indicators of oxidative stress include damaged DNA bases, protein oxidation products, and lipid peroxidation products. The damage to biological tissues is caused by superoxide and other free radicals generated by many factors, including exposure to alcohol, medications, trauma, cold, toxins, and radiation or by antimicrobial cellular immunity, metabolic abnormality, or "normal" aging; not synonymous with hypoxia or hyperoxia. Oxidative stress promotes a range of degenerative disorders, including cancer, diabetes, premature aging, Alzheimer's, and many others. (NCI Thesaurus).

A process that involves tissue structure disintegration and destruction due to action of endogenous or/and exogenous lytic substances which include but not limited to naturally occurring or laboratory designed proteolytic enzymes, glycosidases, detergents, pore-forming proteins, immune complexes, etc. Tissue lysis plays role in pathogenesis of a number of conditions e.g. protozoal infections, ischemic tissue injury, and autoimmune disorders. It is also used as a basis for non-surgical treatment modality to remove or minimize presence of abnormal tissue, e.g. adhesions. (NCI).
A process by which a growth of a tumor involving either an increase in size of a continuous tumor tissue mass or translocation of tumor cells to secondary sites. (NCI).
A process that is a pathologic process in which alterations at the molecular level result in a more aggressive cytologic and phenotypic profile and clinical course of a neoplasm. (NCI).
The process whereby normal tissue cells and structures are replaced by tumor cells. (NCI).
A process that involves inhibition of tumor cell growth, proliferation, malignancy, or metastasis. (NCI).
The process by which waste matter is discharged from the body (nci).

The process of penetration of a substance into a living organism. This process could involve specialized and/or non-specialized mechanisms, active transport or passive movement, and carrier system(s). The common routes of absorption in mammals include the organs of the respiratory and gastrointestinal systems, and the skin. (NCI).
The process of change in the structure and function of an organism that occurs with the passage of time. (NCI).
the process of natural recurring desire for food. (NCI).
The process or act of converting food into chemical substances that can be absorbed and assimilated. (NCI).

A process that involves interference with, or restraint of, hormone release into the bloodstream from endocrine glands. Alteration of positive or negative feedback mechanisms can inhibit hormone release. (NCI).
A process that involves stimulation of hormone release into the bloodstream from endocrine glands. Alteration of positive or negative feedback mechanisms can induce hormone release. (NCI).
The process of evolution of physical movement over an individuals lifespan. (NCI).
The process where thick (myosin) and thin (actin) filaments slide against each other to produce a shortening or tensing of the muscle cell or fiber. (NCI).
A process involving the cells or tissue components of the nervous system. (NCI).
The process of which is consumed to fuel necessary life processes of an organism. (NCI).

A process that involves and promotes the transfer or transmission of stimulatory (sensory) information from the periphery to more central organized structures and mechanisms involved in processing information. (NCI).
The process of a natural and periodic state of rest during which consciousness of the world is suspended. (NCI).
The process by which an offspring is generated by a living organism.
The industria process of sea water desalination.
The tissue of the liver. It includes the hepatic lobules, hepatic sinusoids, perisinusoidal spaces, and portal triad. The hepatic lobules are composed of hepatocytes. (NCI Thesaurus).
All cells in the body of an organism
A cell that is unspecialized, and has the capacity for reproduction through cell division and can be induced to differentiate into a tissue or organ specific cell.
A cell that builds bone, by secretion of an extracellular matrix into which hydroxyapaetite crystals are deposited to form bone.
A cell that degrades bone, by secretion of enzymes in the processes of normal bone remodeling and pathological bone loss. It is a large multinucleated cell   derived from macrophages.
A cell arising from mesenchymal stem cells that produces and is surrounded by the extracellular matrix of cartilage.
A cell forming the majority of the lining of blood and lymph vessels and the inner layer of the endocardium.
A cell in the connective tissue, that makes and secretes collagen proteins.

A star-shaped cell in the liver associated with the development of fibrosis. When stellate cells are activated in response to an injury, they proliferate and synthesize large amounts of extracellular matrix which results in deposition of scar or fibrous tissue.

A cell in the nervous system, that is able to conduct weak electric signals between the brain and the body. A typical neuron consists of a cell body, containing the nucleus and the surrounding cytoplasm (perikaryon); several short radiating processes (dendrites); and one long process (the axon), which terminates in twiglike branches (telodendrons) and may have branches (collaterals) projecting along its course. (NCI).

A connective tissue cell with the ability to convert chemical energy into mechanical energy via a contractile apparatus. As part of the contractile apparatus, the proteins actin and myosin form parallel myofilaments. The interaction of actin and myosin mediates muscle cell contraction in response to stimulation of the excitable cell membrane.
A cell in the blood, that specializes in oxygen transport, has a high concentration of hemoglobin in the cytoplasm and little else.
A cel in the blood, that is devoid of hemoglobin, capable of ameboid motion and phagocytosis, and acts as the principal components of the immune system.
A fragment of a large bone marrow cell (megakaryocyte) which is present in the blood but is not a blood cell. It is an irregular, disc-shaped element in the blood that assists in blood clotting.
A cell of the hematopoietic tissue, that contain coarse, basophilic, metachromatic granules. It is believed to contain heparin and histamine and derive from hematopoietic progenitor cells.
A cell that composes the bulk of the islets of Langerhans in the pancreas and secretes insulin.
A cell that supports the peripheral nervous system that form the myelin sheaths of peripheral nervous system axons.
A cell formed in the first stages of embryonic development, after the splitting of the fertilized ovum, but before the formation of the blastula or blastocyst.
A cell that is located in the epithelium, which covers the body and lines its cavities and glands. (NCI)
A cell with a membrane-bound nucleus, which defines eukaryotic organisms.
A cell in the connective tissue, that synthesizes and stores lipids as energy source. It forms the majority of adipose tissue (fat tissue).

An organelle within the cell, that is known as the powerhouse of the cell. It produces energy-rich molecules (ATP) and regulates the metabolism in the cell. It is  a semiautonomous, self-reproducing organelle that occurs in the cytoplasm of all cells in most eukaryotes.
Materials that are discarded following industrial processes. (NCI)
The material discharged from the bowel during defecation. It consists of undigested food, intestinal mucus, epithelial cells, and bacteria.
The innermost region of the adrenal gland, surrounded by the adrenal cortex.

The outer region of the adrenal gland consisting of the zona glomerulosa, the zona fasciculata, and the zona reticularis. The adrenal cortex produces and secretes mineralocorticoids, glucocorticoids, and adrenal androgens. (NCI).
A process that consists of inspiration, or taking ambient air into the lungs, and expiration, or expelling modified air that contains more carbon dioxide than the air taken in. (NCI).
The process of transporting substances across a biological membrane from an area of higher concentration to an area of lower concentration by means of a carrier molecule. (NCI).

The process of transporting substances across a biological membrane where the flux rate of the diffusing material is controlled by the permeability of the membrane, which in turn is dictated by the size of the pores. (NCI).

The region of the plasma membrane that includes the basal end and sides of the cell. Often used in reference to animal polarized epithelial membranes, where the basal membrane is the part attached to the extracellular matrix, or in plant cells, where the basal membrane is defined with respect to the zygotic axis. (Gene Ontology).
A cellular process that consists of synthesis or breakdown of lipid molecules for energy or storage.
A chemical substance that helps to maintain the proper rhythmicity of genes and proteins affecting the circadian rhythm.

A pervasive developmental disorder that is a spectrum of psychological conditions. The disease includes symptoms of widespread abnormalities of social interactions and communication, severely restricted interests, and highly repetitive behavior.
